T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Cho, J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Carbon-Coated Single-Crystal LiMn<sub>2</sub>O<sub>4</sub> Nanoparticle Clusters as Cathode Material for High-Energy and High-Power Lithium-Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Angew. Chem.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2012</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>124</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">35</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">8878</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">8882</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/ange.201203581</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D124%26publication_year%3D2012%26pages%3D8878-8882%26journal%3DAngew.%2BChem.%26issue%3D35%26author%3DS.%2BLee%26author%3DY.%2BCho%26author%3DH.-K.%2BSong%26author%3DK.%2BT.%2BLee%26author%3DJ.%2BCho%26title%3DCarbon-Coated%2BSingle-Crystal%2BLiMn2O4%2BNanoparticle%2BClusters%2Bas%2BCathode%2BMaterial%2Bfor%2BHigh-Energy%2Band%2BHigh-Power%2BLithium-Ion%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1002%252Fange.201203581&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1002%2Fange.201203581&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord empty" id="
                            cas_R
                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref3"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref3'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">3</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit3" data-doi="10.1038/nmat2418"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Sun, Y.-K.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Myung, S.-T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Park, B.-C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Prakash, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Belharouak, I.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Amine, K.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">High-energy Cathode Material for Long-life and Safe Lithium Batteries</span>. <i>Nat. Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2009</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>8</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">4</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">320</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">324</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1038/nmat2418</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D8%26publication_year%3D2009%26pages%3D320-324%26journal%3DNat.%2BMater.%26issue%3D4%26author%3DY.-K.%2BSun%26author%3DS.-T.%2BMyung%26author%3DB.-C.%2BPark%26author%3DJ.%2BPrakash%26author%3DI.%2BBelharouak%26author%3DK.%2BAmine%26title%3DHigh-energy%2BCathode%2BMaterial%2Bfor%2BLong-life%2Band%2BSafe%2BLithium%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1038%252Fnmat2418&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1038%2Fnmat2418&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit3R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">3</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">High-energy cathode material for long-life and safe lithium batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Sun, Yang-Kook; Myung, Seung-Taek; Park, Byung-Chun; Prakash, Jai; Belharouak, Ilias; Amine, Khalil</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nature Materials</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2009</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">8</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">4</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">320-324</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">NMAACR</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1476-1122</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Nature Publishing Group</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Layered lithium nickel-rich oxides, Li[Ni1-xMx]O2 (M = metal), have attracted significant interest as the cathode material for rechargeable lithium batteries owing to their high capacity, excellent rate capability and low cost.  However, their low thermal-abuse tolerance and poor cycle life, esp. at elevated temp., prohibit their use in practical batteries.  Here, we report on a concn.-gradient cathode material for rechargeable lithium batteries based on a layered lithium nickel cobalt manganese oxide.  In this material, each particle has a central bulk that is rich in Ni and a Mn-rich outer layer with decreasing Ni concn. and increasing Mn and Co concns. as the surface is approached.  The former provides high capacity, whereas the latter improves the thermal stability.  A half cell using our concn.-gradient cathode material achieved a high capacity of 209 mA-h/g and retained 96% of this capacity after 50 charge-discharge cycles under an aggressive test profile (55° between 3.0 and 4.4 V).  Our concn.-gradient material also showed superior performance in thermal-abuse tests compared with the bulk compn. Li[Ni0.8Co0.1Mn0.1]O2 used as ref.  These results suggest that our cathode material could enable prodn. of batteries that meet the demanding performance and safety requirements of plug-in hybrid elec. vehicles.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpdj6x9OC-KubVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhC137r724Big"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD1MXjsFKntrw%253D&amp;md5=a3d00f1540a4bfff34846f105ea2d54d</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref4"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref4'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">4</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit4" data-doi="10.1002/adma.201705575"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shi, J.-L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xiao, D.-D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ge, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yu, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chu, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Huang, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.-D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yin, Y.-X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yang, X.-Q.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Guo, Y.-G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gu, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wan, L.-J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">High-Capacity Cathode Material with High Voltage for Li-Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Adv. Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2018</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>30</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">9</span>), <span class="NLM_elocation-id">1705575</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/adma.201705575</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D30%26publication_year%3D2018%26journal%3DAdv.%2BMater.%26issue%3D9%26author%3DJ.-L.%2BShi%26author%3DD.-D.%2BXiao%26author%3DM.%2BGe%26author%3DX.%2BYu%26author%3DY.%2BChu%26author%3DX.%2BHuang%26author%3DX.-D.%2BZhang%26author%3DY.-X.%2BYin%26author%3DX.-Q.%2BYang%26author%3DY.-G.%2BGuo%26author%3DL.%2BGu%26author%3DL.-J.%2BWan%26title%3DHigh-Capacity%2BCathode%2BMaterial%2Bwith%2BHigh%2BVoltage%2Bfor%2BLi-Ion%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1002%252Fadma.201705575&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1002%2Fadma.201705575&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord empty" id="
                            cas_R
                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref5"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref5'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">5</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit5" data-doi="10.1039/C4EE03029J"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Dunn, J. B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gaines, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Kelly, J. C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">James, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gallagher, K. G.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">The Significance of Li-ion Batteries in Electric Vehicle Life-Cycle Energy and Emissions and Recycling’s Role in its Reduction</span>. <i>Energy Environ. Sci.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2015</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>8</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">1</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">158</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">168</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1039/C4EE03029J</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D8%26publication_year%3D2015%26pages%3D158-168%26journal%3DEnergy%2BEnviron.%2BSci.%26issue%3D1%26author%3DJ.%2BB.%2BDunn%26author%3DL.%2BGaines%26author%3DJ.%2BC.%2BKelly%26author%3DC.%2BJames%26author%3DK.%2BG.%2BGallagher%26title%3DThe%2BSignificance%2Bof%2BLi-ion%2BBatteries%2Bin%2BElectric%2BVehicle%2BLife-Cycle%2BEnergy%2Band%2BEmissions%2Band%2BRecycling%25E2%2580%2599s%2BRole%2Bin%2Bits%2BReduction%26doi%3D10.1039%252FC4EE03029J&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1039%2FC4EE03029J&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit5R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">5</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">The significance of Li-ion batteries in electric vehicle life-cycle energy and emissions and recycling's role in its reduction</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Dunn, J. B.; Gaines, L.; Kelly, J. C.; James, C.; Gallagher, K. G.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Energy &amp; Environmental Science</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2015</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">8</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">1</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">158-168</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">EESNBY</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1754-5706</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Three key questions have driven recent discussions of the energy and environmental impacts of automotive lithium-ion batteries.  We address each of them, beginning with whether the energy intensity of producing all materials used in batteries or that of battery assembly is greater.  Notably, battery assembly energy intensity depends on assembly facility throughput because energy consumption of equipment, esp. the dry room, is mainly throughput-independent.  Low-throughput facilities therefore will have higher energy intensities than near-capacity facilities.  In our anal., adopting an assembly energy intensity reflective of a low-throughput plant caused the assembly stage to dominate cradle-to-gate battery energy and environmental impact results.  Results generated with an at-capacity assembly plant energy intensity, however, indicated cathode material prodn. and aluminum use as a structural material were the drivers.  Ests. of cradle-to-gate battery energy and environmental impacts must therefore be interpreted in light of assumptions made about assembly facility throughput.  The second key question is whether battery recycling is worthwhile if battery assembly dominates battery cradle-to-gate impacts.  In this case, even if recycled cathode materials are less energy and emissions intensive than virgin cathode materials, little energy and environmental benefit is obtained from their use because the energy consumed in assembly is so high.  We reviewed the local impacts of metals recovery for cathode materials and concluded that avoiding or reducing these impacts, including SOx emissions and water contamination, is a key motivator of battery recycling regardless of the energy intensity of assembly.  Finally, we address whether elec. vehicles (EV) offer improved energy and environmental performance compared to internal combustion-engine vehicles (ICV).  This anal. illustrated that, even if a battery assembly energy reflective of a low-throughput facility is adopted, EVs consume less petroleum and emit fewer greenhouse gases (GHG) than an ICV on a life-cycle basis.  The only scenario in which an EV emitted more GHGs than an ICV was when it used solely coal-derived electricity as a fuel source.  SOx emissions, however, were up to four times greater for EVs than ICVs.  These emissions could be reduced through battery recycling.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGret76te8bENrVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0li3jg81gULkUw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2cXhvV2mtL3P&amp;md5=4dc88d7068d183d656e2ec3314cc9e58</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref6"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref6'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">6</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit6" data-doi="10.1016/j.ensm.2021.02.032"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Costa, C.                         cas_cit10R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">10</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Towards K-Ion and Na-Ion Batteries as "Beyond Li-Ion"</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Kubota, Kei; Dahbi, Mouad; Hosaka, Tomooki; Kumakura, Shinichi; Komaba, Shinichi</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Record</span>

    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">18</span>

        </div><div class="casAbstract">A review.  Li-ion battery commercialized by Sony in 1991 has the highest energy-d. among practical rechargeable batteries and is widely used in electronic devices, elec. vehicles, and stationary energy storage system in the world.  Moreover, the battery market is rapidly growing in the world and further fast-growing is expected.  With expansion of the demand and applications, price of lithium and cobalt resources is increasing.  We are, therefore, motivated to study Na- and K-ion batteries for stationary energy storage system because of much abundant Na and K resources and the wide distribution in the world.  In this account, we review developments of Na- and K-ion batteries with mainly introducing our previous and present researches in comparison to that of Li-ion battery.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoSYlvjIhnmwLVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lh2cLtsk-HQaw"> &gt;&gt;                         cas_cit11R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">11</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Tuning crystal structure and redox potential of NASICON-type cathodes for sodium-ion batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Ma, Xuemei; Cao, Xinxin; Zhou, Yifan; Guo, Shan; Shi, Xiaodong; Fang, Guozhao; Pan, Anqiang; Lu, Bingan; Zhou, Jiang; Liang, Shuquan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nano Research</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2020</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">13</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">12</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">3330-3337</span>CODEN:

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Springer GmbH</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium superionic conductor (NASICON)-type compds. have been regarded as promising cathodes for sodium-ion batteries (SIBs) due to their favorable ionic cond. and robust structural stability.  However, their high cost and relatively low energy d. restrict their further practical application, which can be tailored by widening the operating voltages with earth-abundant elements such as Mn.  Here, we propose a rational strategy of infusing Mn element in NASICON frameworks with sufficiently mobile sodium ions that enhances the redox voltage and ionic migration activity.  The optimized structure of Na3.5Mn0.5V1.5(PO4)3/C is achieved and investigated systematically to be a durable cathode (76.6% capacity retention over 5,000 cycles at 20 C) for SIBs, which exhibits high reversible capacity (113.1 mAh·g-1 at 0.5 C) with relatively low vol. change (7.6%).  Importantly, its high-areal-loading and temp.-resistant sodium ion storage properties are evaluated, and the full-cell configuration is demonstrated.  This work indicates that this Na3.5Mn0.5V1.5(PO4)3/C composite could be a promising cathode candidate for SIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrjespGri5z6bVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lh2cLtsk-HQaw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3cXitVWrs7jM&amp;md5=0b5cc8fe989d085f223643702c692210</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref12"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref12'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">12</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit12" data-doi="10.1146/annurev-physchem-040513-103644"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wyttenbach, T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Pierson, N.                         cas_cit12R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">12</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Ion mobility analysis of molecular dynamics</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Wyttenbach, Thomas; Pierson, Nicholas A.; Clemmer, David E.; Bowers, Michael T.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Annual Review of Physical Chemistry</span>

    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">175-196</span>CODEN:

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Annual Reviews</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A review.  The combination of mass spectrometry and ion mobility spectrometry (IMS) employing a temp.-variable drift cell or a drift tube divided into sections to make IMS-IMS expts. possible allows information to be obtained about the mol. dynamics of polyat. ions in the absence of a solvent.  The expts. allow the investigation of structural changes of both activated and native ion populations on a timescale of 1-100 ms.  Five different systems representing small and large, polar and nonpolar mols., as well as noncovalent assemblies, are discussed in detail: a dinucleotide, a sodiated polyethylene glycol chain, the peptide bradykinin, the protein ubiquitin, and two types of peptide oligomers.  Barriers to conformational interconversion can be obtained in favorable cases.  In other cases, soln.-like native structures can be obsd., but care must be taken in the exptl. protocols.  The power of theor. modeling is demonstrated.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGodqjrP5GsbR7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lh2cLtsk-HQaw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2cXhtVKjtLvO&amp;md5=a5f03a8a245e3c361571bfb103adf391</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref13"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref13'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">13</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit13" data-doi="10.1039/C7CC00301C"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jian, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Rodríguez-Pérez, I.                 10.1039/C7CC00301C</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D53%26publication_year%3D2017%26pages%3D2610-2613%26journal%3DChem.%2BCommun.%26issue%3D17%26author%3DZ.%2BLi%26author%3DZ.%2BJian%26author%3DX.%2BWang%26author%3DI.%2BA.%2BRodr%25C3%25ADguez-P%25C3%25A9rez%26author%3DC.%2BBommier%26author%3DX.%2BJi%26title%3DHard%2BCarbon%2BAnodes%2Bof%2BSodium-ion%2BBatteries%253A%2BUndervalued%2BRate%2BCapability%26doi%3D10.1039%252FC7CC00301C&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1039%2FC7CC00301C&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit13R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">13</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Hard carbon anodes of sodium-ion batteries: undervalued rate capability</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Li, Zhifei; Jian, Zelang; Wang, Xingfeng; Rodriguez-Perez, Ismael A.; Bommier, Clement; Ji, Xiulei</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Communications (Cambridge, United Kingdom)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2017</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">53</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">17</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2610-2613</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CHCOFS</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1359-7345</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The rate capability of hard carbon has long been underestimated in prior studies that used carbon/Na two-electrode half-cells.  Through a three-electrode cell setup, we discover that it is the overpotential of the sodium counter electrode that drives the half-cells to the lower cutoff potential prematurely during hard carbon sodiation, particularly at high current rates, which prevents the hard carbon anode from being fully sodiated.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpIWp6wPR34ibVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lh2cLtsk-HQaw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2sXit1Smurk%253D&amp;md5=74cb919d478ce4905e0900d93be660f0</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref14"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref14'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">14</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit14" data-doi="10.1021/acs.accounts.5b00482"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shen, F.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Bommier, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhu, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ji, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Hu, L.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Na-Ion Battery Anodes: Materials and Electrochemistry</span>. <i>Acc. Chem. Res.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2016</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>49</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">2</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">231</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">240</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acs.accounts.5b00482</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D49%26publication_year%3D2016%26pages%3D231-240%26journal%3DAcc.%2BChem.%2BRes.%26issue%3D2%26author%3DW.%2BLuo%26author%3DF.%2BShen%26author%3DC.%2BBommier%26author%3DH.%2BZhu%26author%3DX.%2BJi%26author%3DL.%2BHu%26title%3DNa-Ion%2BBattery%2BAnodes%253A%2BMaterials%2Band%2BElectrochemistry%26doi%3D10.1021%252Facs.accounts.5b00482&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1021%2Facs.accounts.5b00482&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit14R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">14</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Na-Ion Battery Anodes: Materials and Electrochemistry</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Luo, Wei; Shen, Fei; Bommier, Clement; Zhu, Hongli; Ji, Xiulei; Hu, Liangbing</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Accounts of Chemical Research</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2016</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">49</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">2</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">231-240</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ACHRE4</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0001-4842</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The intermittent nature of renewable energy sources, such as solar and wind, calls for sustainable elec. energy storage (EES) technologies for stationary applications.  Li will be simply too rare for Li-ion batteries (LIBs) to be used for large-scale storage purposes.  In contrast, Na-ion batteries (NIBs) are highly promising to meet the demand of grid-level storage because Na is truly earth abundant and ubiquitous around the globe.  Furthermore, NIBs share a similar rocking-chair operation mechanism with LIBs, which potentially provides high reversibility and long cycling life.  It would be most efficient to transfer knowledge learned on LIBs during the last three decades to the development of NIBs.  Following this logic, rapid progress has been made in NIB cathode materials, where layered metal oxides and polyanionic compds. exhibit encouraging results.  On the anode side, pure graphite as the std. anode for LIBs can only form NaC64 in NIBs if solvent co-intercalation does not occur due to the unfavorable thermodn.  In fact, it was the utilization of a carbon anode in LIBs that enabled the com. successes.  Anodes of metal-ion batteries det. key characteristics, such as safety and cycling life; thus, it is indispensable to identify suitable anode materials for NIBs.In this Account, we review recent development on anode materials for NIBs.  Due to the limited space, we will mainly discuss carbon-based and alloy-based anodes and highlight progress made in our groups in this field.  We first present what is known about the failure mechanism of graphite anode in NIBs.  We then go on to discuss studies on hard carbon anodes, alloy-type anodes, and org. anodes.  Esp., the multiple functions of natural cellulose that is used as a low-cost carbon precursor for mass prodn. and as a soft substrate for tin anodes are highlighted.  The strategies of minimizing the surface area of carbon anodes for improving the first-cycle Coulombic efficiency are also outlined, where graphene oxide was employed as dehydration agent and 2,2,6,6-tetramethylpiperidine-1-oxyl (TEMPO) was used to unzip wood fiber.  Furthermore, surface modification by at. layer deposition technol. is introduced, where we discover that a thin layer of Al2O3 can function to encapsulate Sn nanoparticles, leading to a much enhanced cycling performance.  We also highlight recent work about the phosphorene/graphene anode, which outperformed other anodes in terms of capacity.  The arom. org. anode is also studied as anode with very high initial sodiation capacity.  Furthermore, electrochem. intercalation of Na ions into reduced graphene oxide is applied for fabricating transparent conductors, demonstrating the great feasibility of Na ion intercalation for optical applications.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGorKnQvVSK3P7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgk3pihOBK-pA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC28XhtVGksrg%253D&amp;md5=90d2907a2b33fdcf59913255073dd969</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref15"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref15'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">15</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit15" data-doi="10.1016/j.ensm.2018.04.014"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zheng, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Bommier, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jiang, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Hao, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Huang, Y.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Sodium Metal Anodes for Room-temperature Sodium-ion batteries: Applications, Challenges and Solutions</span>. <i>Energy Storage Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>16</i></span>,  <span class="NLM_fpage">6</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">23</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:

                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref16"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref16'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">16</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit16" data-doi="10.1016/j.nanoen.2018.03.039"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Tang, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Qiu, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, X.-Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gu, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.-G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, W.-W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yan, J.-W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zheng, M.-S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Dong, Q.-F.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mao, B.-W.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Room-temperature Sodium Metal Anode Enabled by a Sodiophilic Layer</span>. <i>Nano Energy</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2018</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>48</i></span>,  <span class="NLM_fpage">101</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">106</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1016/j.nanoen.2018.03.039</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D48%26publication_year%3D2018%26pages%3D101-106%26journal%3DNano%2BEnergy%26author%3DS.%2BTang%26author%3DZ.%2BQiu%26author%3DX.-Y.%2BWang%26author%3DY.%2BGu%26author%3DX.-G.%2BZhang%26author%3DW.-W.%2BWang%26author%3DJ.-W.%2BYan%26author%3DM.-S.%2BZheng%26author%3DQ.-F.%2BDong%26author%3DB.-W.%2BMao%26title%3DA%2BRoom-temperature%2BSodium%2BMetal%2BAnode%2BEnabled%2Bby%2Ba%2BSodiophilic%2BLayer%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.nanoen.2018.03.039&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.nanoen.2018.03.039&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit16R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">16</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A room-temperature sodium metal anode enabled by a sodiophilic layer</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Tang, Shuai; Qiu, Zhi; Wang, Xue-Yin; Gu, Yu; Zhang, Xia-Guang; Wang, Wei-Wei; Yan, Jia-Wei; Zheng, Ming-Sen; Dong, Quan-Feng; Mao, Bing-Wei</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nano Energy</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2018</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">48</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">101-106</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">NEANCA</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2211-2855</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier Ltd.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium metal is a very promising anode for energy storage and conversion in the post lithium ion battery era because of its high capacity (1166 mA h g-1), earth-abundance and low cost.  However, the sodium metal anode suffers from unstable plating and stripping cycling and thus low Coulombic efficiency.  One of the important reasons for the situation is the high overpotential for sodium nucleation and thus non-uniform deposition and even dendrites growth.  Herein we report a facile method by introducing a "sodiophilic" layer of Au-Na alloy onto the Cu substrate that acts as the current collector to significantly reduce the nucleation overpotential.  Thus, the sodium metal can be plated on and stripped from the modified current collector with good reversibility.  The av. Coulombic efficiency maintains 99.8% at the current of 2.0 mA cm-2 for 300 cycles.  As a proof of concept, an anode-free full cell consisting of Cu@Au and presodiated FeS2 was assembled.  Our work demonstrates the great importance of sodiophilic modification of substrate to the deposition process for sodium metal battery.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGreep3WCW-hI7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgk3pihOBK-pA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXmtVahtbs%253D&amp;md5=f627a7151f1307f7360f84a4b346ca2a</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref17"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref17'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">17</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit17" data-doi="10.1021/acs.chemrev.8b00642"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Lee, B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Paek, E.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mitlin, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Lee, S. W.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Sodium Metal Anodes: Emerging Solutions to Dendrite Growth</span>. <i>Chem. Rev.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>119</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">8</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">5416</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">5460</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acs.chemrev.8b00642</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D119%26publication_year%3D2019%26pages%3D5416-5460%26journal%3DChem.%2BRev.%26issue%3D8%26author%3DB.%2BLee%26author%3DE.%2BPaek%26author%3DD.%2BMitlin%26author%3DS.%2BW.%2BLee%26title%3DSodium%2BMetal%2BAnodes%253A%2BEmerging%2BSolutions%2Bto%2BDendrite%2BGrowth%26doi%3D10.1021%252Facs.chemrev.8b00642&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1021%2Facs.chemrev.8b00642&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit17R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">17</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Sodium metal anodes: Emerging solutions to dendrite growth</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Lee, Byeongyong; Paek, Eunsu; Mitlin, David; Lee, Seung Woo</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Reviews (Washington, DC, United States)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">119</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">8</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">5416-5460</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CHREAY</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0009-2665</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">This comprehensive Review focuses on the key challenges and recent progress regarding sodium-metal anodes employed in sodium-metal batteries (SMBs).  The metal anode is the essential component of emerging energy storage systems such as sodium sulfur and sodium selenium, which are discussed as example full-cell applications.  We begin with a description of the differences in the chem. and phys. properties of Na metal vs. the oft-studied Li metal, and a corresponding discussion regarding the no. of ways in which Na does not follow Li-inherited paradigms in its electrochem. behavior.  We detail the major challenges for Na-metal systems that at this time limit the feasibility of SMBs.  The core Na anode problems are the following interrelated degrdn. mechanisms: An unstable solid electrolyte interphase with most org. electrolytes, "mossy" and "lath-like" metal dendrite growth for liq. systems, poor Coulombic efficiency, and gas evolution.  Even solid-state Na batteries are not immune, with metal dendrites being reported.  The solns. may be subdivided into the following interrelated taxonomy: Improved electrolytes and electrolyte additives tailored for Na-metal anodes, interfacial engineering between the metal and the liq. or solid electrolyte, electrode architectures that both reduce the c.d. during plating-stripping and serve as effective hosts that shield the Na metal from excessive reactions, and alloy design to tune the bulk properties of the metal per se.  For instance, stable plating-stripping of Na is extremely difficult with conventional carbonate solvents but has been reported with ethers and glymes.  Solid-state electrolytes (SSEs) such as beta-alumina solid electrolyte (BASE), sodium superionic conductor (NASICON), and sodium thiophosphate (75Na2S·25P2S5) present highly exciting opportunities for SMBs that avoid the dangers of flammable liqs.  Even SSEs are not immune to dendrites, however, which grow through the defects in the bulk pellet, but may be controlled through interfacial energy modification.  We conclude with a discussion of the key research areas that we feel are the most fruitful for further pursuit.  In our opinion, greatly improved understanding and control of the SEI structure is the key to cycling stability.  A holistic approach involving complementary post-mortem, in situ, and operando analyses to elucidate full battery cell level structure-performance relations is advocated.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqQ1buYt3eMx7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgk3pihOBK-pA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1MXmsFCrtL4%253D&amp;md5=50399f6bff0463f55ea84f50d36fb802</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref18"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref18'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">18</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit18" data-doi="10.1021/acs.accounts.9b00437"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, A.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Dendrites in Lithium Metal Anodes: Suppression, Regulation, and Elimination</span>. <i>Acc. Chem. Res.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>52</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">11</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">3223</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">3232</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acs.accounts.9b00437</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D52%26publication_year%3D2019%26pages%3D3223-3232%26journal%3DAcc.%2BChem.%2BRes.%26issue%3D11%26author%3DX.%2BZhang%26author%3DA.%2BWang%26author%3DX.%2BLiu%26author%3DJ.%2BLuo%26title%3DDendrites%2Bin%2BLithium%2BMetal%2BAnodes%253A%2BSuppression%252C%2BRegulation%252C%2Band%2BElimination%26doi%3D10.1021%252Facs.accounts.9b00437&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1021%2Facs.accounts.9b00437&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit18R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">18</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Dendrites in Lithium Metal Anodes: Suppression, Regulation, and Elimination</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Zhang, Xinyue; Wang, Aoxuan; Liu, Xingjiang; Luo, Jiayan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Accounts of Chemical Research</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">52</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">11</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">3223-3232</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ACHRE4</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0001-4842</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A review is given.  With the increasing diversification of portable electronics and large-scale energy storage systems, conventional Li-ion batteries (LIBs) with graphite anodes are now approaching their theor. limits.  Li metal, as the Holy Grail electrode for next-generation rechargeable batteries, is being revisited to meet the booming demand for high energy d. electrodes due to its ultrahigh theor. specific capacity and neg. redox potential.  Nevertheless, typical issues like notorious dendrite growth still hamper the bulk application of Li metal anodes.  Dendrite growth renders increased surface area of the Li metal, causing persistent depletion of the electrolyte and active materials, facilitating catastrophic failure of the battery, and even inducing fatal safety hazards.  The consequences become more serious during operation at high current densities and over long cycling life.  Therefore, it is urgent to suppress and even eliminate dendrite formation during the Li plating/stripping process.  This Account highlights several innovative strategies for dendrite suppression, dendrite regulation, and dendrite elimination from the perspective of interface energy and bulk stresses.  We review the fundamental mechanism of dendrite formation and growth in Li metal anodes.  We show that the dendrite morphol. could be substantially ameliorated, in theory, by homogenizing the elec. field distribution, lowering the Li ion concn. gradient, and facilitating mech. blocking.  We address the problem of dendrite suppression by applying 2-dimensional (2D) materials to Li metal systems and preventing dendrite penetration through stress release and mech. blocking.  Graphene with a high specific area and vermiculite sheets (VSs) with a large phys. rigidity were demonstrated to be efficacious in reinforcing Li anodes and polymer electrolytes sep.  However, Li dendrite growth is a continuous process and remains inevitable with increasing c.d. and cycling life.  Instead of suppressing dendrite growth, we focus on how to regulate homogeneous Li dendrite formation and growth.  Dendrite regulation means to allow dendrite growth but take steps to transform it into Li with a smooth morphol.  We introduce 2 main strategies to regulate Li growth: (1) guiding Li nucleation and (2) controlling the Li growth pathways and directions.  These processes greatly rely on the interface energy between the substrate and Li atoms.  Elimination of the dendrites, which is the most formidable challenge for dendrite control, can also be achieved by dynamically engineering the force, such as deflecting the elec. field by Lorentz force in a magnetic field, enhancing the integrated yield stress by the design of bulk nanostructured materials, and reducing the lateral Li diffusion barrier by a biomimetic co-deposition process.  Solns. to the challenges of dendrite control in Li metal anodes can provide safe next-generation rechargeable Li metal batteries that have a long cycling life.  We also hope that our strategies presented in this account can offer promise for other metal batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqTmYiRWVzgprVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgk3pihOBK-pA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1MXitVaku7nJ&amp;md5=afb52f2ba1a27739ed738db2108458a2</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref19"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref19'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">19</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit19" data-doi="10.1039/D0TA11828A"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jia, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Dirican, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Qiu, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chan, C. Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Fu, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Fei, B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Liquid Metal Assisted Dendrite-free Anode for High-performance Zn-ion Batteries</span>. <i>J. Mater. Chem. A</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2021</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>9</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">9</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">5597</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">5605</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1039/D0TA11828A</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D9%26publication_year%3D2021%26pages%3D5597-5605%26journal%3DJ.%2BMater.%2BChem.%2BA%26issue%3D9%26author%3DH.%2BJia%26author%3DZ.%2BWang%26author%3DM.%2BDirican%26author%3DS.%2BQiu%26author%3DC.%2BY.%2BChan%26author%3DS.%2BFu%26author%3DB.%2BFei%26author%3DX.%2BZhang%26title%3DA%2BLiquid%2BMetal%2BAssisted%2BDendrite-free%2BAnode%2Bfor%2BHigh-performance%2BZn-ion%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1039%252FD0TA11828A&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1039%2FD0TA11828A&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit19R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">19</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A liquid metal assisted dendrite-free anode for high-performance Zn-ion batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Jia, Hao; Wang, Ziqi; Dirican, Mahmut; Qiu, Sheng; Chan, Cheuk Ying; Fu, Shaohai; Fei, Bin; Zhang, Xiangwu</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Materials Chemistry A: Materials for Energy and Sustainability</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2021</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">9</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">9</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">5597-5605</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JMCAET</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2050-7496</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Zinc metal is a promising anode candidate due to its high theor. capacity and high abundance, making aq. zinc ion batteries (ZIBs) some of the most promising energy storage systems for large scale grids.  However, the practical application of ZIBs is seriously inhibited by detrimental dendrite growth on the zinc metal anode surface.  To tackle this problem, we propose a scalable approach for preventing dendrite formation by introducing a liq. Ga-In-Zn alloy as a self-healing protective layer on zinc anodes.  The as-established liq. metal (LM) layer serves as an effective liq.-state diffusion barrier and accelerates Zn nucleation speed and electron transfer.  Compared to the traditional solid-liq. interface of solid electrodes, the stable liq.-liq. interface between the LM and electrolyte enables better charge transfer kinetics and thus significantly reduces the interfacial resistance by 98.4%.  The decreased Zn ion migration barrier energy after LM coating was also confirmed by d. functional theory calcn.  More impressively, the LM ensures an ultralong cycling life of 10 000 cycles by enabling dendrite-free Zn deposition due to its high fluidity and deformability.  Consequently, our work suggests a novel strategy to modify the Zn anodes in ZIBs by inhibiting dendrite formation and promote future applications for a sufficient work span.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGp4p0iofZgIjrVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgk3pihOBK-pA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3MXhsVGjsLw%253D&amp;md5=3299e9bae1d1464d945b237d20276c37</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref20"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref20'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">20</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit20" data-doi="10.1002/adma.201602633"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, L.                         cas_cit22R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">22</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Semi-Solid CNT@NaK Anode for Potassium Metal Battery</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Yuan, Wenlu; Ding, Taifeng; Mou, Peizhi; Luo, Yusheng; Li, Laiping; Chen, Yong; Chen, Xiumin; Shu, Jie; Zhang, Liyuan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Advanced Functional Materials</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),

        </div><div class="casAbstract">The CK bond plays a significant role in stabilizing the Na-K (NaK) alloy electrodes due to the enhancive interfacial affinity.  In this study, a method for constructing semi-solid K metal electrodes with rich CK bonds by in situ replacement of N-doped carbon nanotubes (CNT) and liq. NaK alloy is proposed.  Based on the in situ IR thermal imaging technique combined with heat calcn., XPS elemental anal., and reaction thermodn. calcn., graphite-N, which is widely distributed on the wall of CNT, offers plenty of replacement sites for forming CK bonds.  Due to the rich bonds, the amt. of CNT sharply reduces in dendrite-free semi-solid CNT@NaK electrodes and the activity of NaK alloy raises to ≈90%.  This discovery provides a new idea for establishing dendrite-free anodes for K metal batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqjxaQd_DzT1rVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lixj76lb5GkMQ"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB38XivFOnu7vE&amp;md5=9ba5847aa92e0d2affd3cb26d844aa68</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref23"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref23'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">23</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit23" data-doi="10.1016/j.jechem.2022.03.027"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yuan, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ye, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Huang, Q.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Fu, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wu, Y.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Advances on Na-K Liquid Alloy-based Batteries</span>. <i>J.                 10.1016/j.jechem.2022.03.027</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D71%26publication_year%3D2022%26pages%3D313-323%26journal%3DJ.%2BEnergy%2BChem.%26author%3DJ.%2BWu%26author%3DZ.%2BXue%26author%3DL.%2BYuan%26author%3DJ.%2BYe%26author%3DQ.%2BHuang%26author%3DL.%2BFu%26author%3DY.%2BWu%26title%3DAdvances%2Bon%2BNa-K%2BLiquid%2BAlloy-based%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.jechem.2022.03.027&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.jechem.2022.03.027&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit23R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">23</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Advances on Na-K liquid alloy-based batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Wu, Junwei; Xue, Zhuang; Yuan, Lixuan; Ye, Jilei; Huang, Qinghong; Fu, Lijun; Wu, Yuping</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Energy Chemistry</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2022</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">71</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">313-323</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JECOFG</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2095-4956</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Science Press</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A review.  Sodium-potassium (Na-K) liq. alloys attract increasing research attention, as an ideal alternative of Li metal for metal-based batteries, attributing to their high abundance, low redox potential, high capacity, and dendrite-free properties. In addn., the liq. and self-healing features of Na-K alloys endow good electrode/electrolyte interfacial contact. The recent advances on the Na-K liq. alloy-based batteries (NKBs) are reviewed herein. The anode designs for immobilization of the liq. alloy are introduced. The influences of the electrolyte and cathode materials on the battery performances are discussed. In addn., considering the co-existence of both K+ and Na+ in the electrolyte, the working mechanisms of the NKBs are elaborated. We also show that despite the improvement, challenges of the NKBs remain. The compatibility between Na-K liq. alloy and electrolyte, as well as disputed working mechanisms, request detailed surface analyses of the liq. alloy and local element distribution evolution in the battery. This review would shed light on the fundamental understanding of Na-K alloy electrochem. and the development of dendrite-free metal-based energy storage systems with high energy d.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoYT2sE2PwlTbVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lixj76lb5GkMQ"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB38XisFOis7jI&amp;md5=afae0015383a22be4c09f6c13035deb8</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref24"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref24'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">24</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit24" data-doi="10.1002/anie.201809622"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhou, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xin, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gao, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhou, A.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Goodenough, J. B.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Room-Temperature Liquid Na–K Anode Membranes</span>. <i>Angew. Chem., Int. Ed.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2018</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>57</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">43</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">14184</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">14187</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/anie.201809622</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D57%26publication_year%3D2018%26pages%3D14184-14187%26journal%3DAngew.%2BChem.%252C%2BInt.%2BEd.%26issue%3D43%26author%3DL.%2BXue%26author%3DW.%2BZhou%26author%3DS.%2BXin%26author%3DH.%2BGao%26author%3DY.%2BLi%26author%3DA.%2BZhou%26author%3DJ.%2BB.%2BGoodenough%26title%3DRoom-Temperature%2BLiquid%2BNa%25E2%2580%2593K%2BAnode%2BMembranes%26doi%3D10.1002%252Fanie.201809622&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1002%2Fanie.201809622&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit24R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">24</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Room-Temperature Liquid Na-K Anode Membranes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Xue, Leigang; Zhou, Weidong; Xin, Sen; Gao, Hongcai; Li, Yutao; Zhou, Aijun; Goodenough, John B.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Angewandte Chemie, International Edition</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2018</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">57</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">43</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">14184-14187</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ACIEF5</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1433-7851</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The Na-K alloy is a liq. at 25° over a large compositional range.  The liq. alloy is also immiscible in the org.-liq. electrolytes of an alkali-ion rechargeable battery, providing dendrite-free liq. alkali-metal batteries with a liq.-liq. anode-electrolyte interface at room temp.  The two liqs. are each immobilized in a porous matrix.  In previous work, the porous matrix used to immobilize the alloy was a carbon paper that is wet by the alloy at 420°; the alloy remains in the paper at room temp.  Here we report a room-temp. vacuum infiltration of the alloy into a porous Cu or Al membrane and a reversible stripping/plating of the liq. alloy with the immobilized org.-liq. electrolyte; no self-diacharge is obsd. since the liq. Na-K does not dissolve into the liq. carbonate electrolytes.  The prepn. and stripping/plating of the liq. alkali-metal anode can both now be done safely at room temp.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoaV0b5np9qr7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lixj76lb5GkMQ"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXhvVKqu7rN&amp;md5=dc133e61e1222cbf5d0643a7ffecd816</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref25"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref25'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">25</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit25" data-doi="10.1002/sstr.202300097"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Cheng, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Lin, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, M.-S.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Na–K Co-Deposition In Liquid-Alloy Batteries Revealed by Operando Visualization</span>. <i>Small Struct.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2023</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>4</i></span>, <span class="NLM_elocation-id">2300097</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/sstr.202300097</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D4%26publication_year%3D2023%26journal%3DSmall%2BStruct.%26author%3DY.%2BCheng%26author%3DC.%2BLin%26author%3DC.%2BLuo%26author%3DW.%2BLiu%26author%3DM.-S.%2BWang%26title%3DNa%25E2%2580%2593K%2BCo-Deposition%2BIn%2BLiquid-Alloy%2BBatteries%2BRevealed%2Bby%2BOperando%2BVisualization%26doi%3D10.1002%252Fsstr.202300097&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1002%2Fsstr.202300097&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit25R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">25</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Na-K Co-deposition in Liquid-Alloy Batteries Revealed by Operando Visualization</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Cheng, Yong; Lin, Chenxue; Luo, Chong; Liu, Weicheng; Wang, Ming-Sheng</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Small Structures</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">4</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">11</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2300097</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">SSMTB2</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2688-4062</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Despite the great prospects of alkali metal batteries, safety concerns assocd. with dendrite growth still limit their com. applications.  An attractive alternative is to use the room temp. liq. sodium-potassium alloy as the anode, which inherently prevents dendrite growth.  Currently, Na-K alloy anodes allow only Na+ or K+ to be cycled, depending on the choice of electrolyte and ion selectivity of the cathode, which results in reduced energy d. of the battery.  Herein, the possibility of concurrent use of both Na+ and K+ ions in Na-K alloy anodes is explored, and the working mechanism by operando optical microscopy is investigated.  It is found that the type of deposited metal is dictated by both salt and solvent in electrolyte.  Impressively, Na-K co-deposition is obsd. in KFSI-DME electrolyte for the first time, which strongly influences the dendrite morphol. and evolution.  Furthermore, the c.d. also has a great impact on the deposition pattern, which allows dendrite-free Na/K deposition on the liq.-alloy anode.  These findings enrich our understanding of the intricate electrochem. behaviors of Na-K binary electroactive alloy systems and offer guidance for the sufficient use of Na and K while avoiding dendrite formation in such liq.-alloy batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrHKRXzkHZmILVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0liimcxnVrZbyA"> &gt;&gt;                         cas_cit26R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">26</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Suitability of NaK alloy for the sodium or potassium metal batteries: Competition between cathode size effect and ion reaction priority effect</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Ding, Taifeng; Chen, Yong; Yuan, Wenlu; Li, Laiping; Mou, Peizhi; Luo, Yusheng; Yu, Haoxiang; Yan, Lei; Shu, Jie; Zhang, Liyuan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Engineering Journal (Amsterdam, Netherlands)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">475</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">146185</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CMEJAJ</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1385-8947</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier B.V.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium-potassium (NaK) alloys in a specific ratio can maintain their liq. state at room temp., rendering them dendrite-free anodes for alkali metal batteries.  Nevertheless, a controversy has arisen regarding the suitability of either sodium metal batteries (NaMBs) or potassium metal batteries (KMBs) due to the presence of dual active ions in NaK.  Based on the current research, there is a contradiction regarding the feasibility of making NaK anodes suitable for NaMBs through the cathode size effect (e.g., Na3V2(PO4)3), and for KMBs due to the ion reaction priority effect of K+.  In this study, Na3V2(PO4)3 (NVP) cathodes are assembled into batteries with various anodes (Na, Na-rich-NaK, NaK, K-rich-NaK, and K), to investigate the dominant role of active ions in the competing process between the cathode size effect and the ion reaction priority effect.  Tests and characterization results demonstrate that the ion preference reaction spontaneously displaces Na+ with K+ in the presence of K, although the cathode size effect may restrict K+ embedding and significantly reduce battery capacity.  In summary, the ion reaction priority effect dictates the reactions that render NaK anodes exclusively suitable for KMBs without altering the reaction priority of K+.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqK88l6voBJILVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0liimcxnVrZbyA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhvFyqs7nI&amp;md5=ccf85f7b48f238ee6fe7b46732c374e6</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref27"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref27'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">27</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit27" data-doi="10.1039/C9EE00437H"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Peng, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ding, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Guo, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Qian, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Celio, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">He, G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yu, G.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Graphite Intercalation Compound Associated with Liquid Na–K Towards Ultra-Stable and High-capacity Alkali Metal Anodes</span>. <i>Energy Environ.                         cas_cit27R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">27</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A graphite intercalation compound associated with liquid Na-K towards ultra-stable and high-capacity alkali metal anodes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Zhang, Leyuan; Peng, Sangshan; Ding, Yu; Guo, Xuelin; Qian, Yumin; Celio, Hugo; He, Gaohong; Yu, Guihua</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Energy &amp; Environmental Science</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">12</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">6</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">1989-1998</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">EESNBY</span>;

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Alkali metal anodes (Li, Na, K) are highly promising for enabling high-energy-d. rechargeable batteries due to their high theor. capacities and low redox potentials.  Although extensive studies have been performed on Li-metal, dendrite growth and serious interface issues are still fundamental challenges for practical alkali metal batteries (AMBs).  Here, we report an in situ-formed graphite intercalation compd. (GIC) framework that enables Na-K liq. alloy to be used in ultra-stable and high-capacity anodes, attributed to the synergy of fast electron and mass transport of the GIC networks assocd. with the self-healing behavior of the Na-K alloy.  The Na-K composite electrode is highly stable; it sustains repeated stripping/deposition over 5000 h at 20 mA cm-2 and achieves stable electrodeposition even at 80 mA cm-2 and 16 mA h cm-2.  When coupled with various cathodes, versatile AMBs are realized with long cycling and high operating voltages.  This framework electrode design presents new insight into developing dendrite-free alkali metal anodes.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGp4LJL9OORkc7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0liimcxnVrZbyA"> &gt;&gt;
