                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref29"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref29'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">29</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit29" data-doi="10.1002/advs.202206479"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Cui, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jin, B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xu, A.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shao, M.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Single-atom Metallophilic Sites for Liquid NaK Alloy Confinement toward Stable Alkali-metal Anodes</span>. <i>Adv. Sci.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2023</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>10</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">8</span>), <span class="NLM_elocation-id">2206479</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/advs.202206479</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D10%26publication_year%3D2023%26journal%3DAdv.%2BSci.%26issue%3D8%26author%3DJ.%2BCui%26author%3DB.%2BJin%26author%3DA.%2BXu%26author%3DJ.%2BLi%26author%3DM.%2BShao%26title%3DSingle-atom%2BMetallophilic%2BSites%2Bfor%2BLiquid%2BNaK%2BAlloy%2BConfinement%2Btoward%2BStable%2BAlkali-metal%2BAnodes%26doi%3D10.1002%252Fadvs.202206479&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1002%2Fadvs.202206479&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit29R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">29</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Single-Atom Metallophilic Sites for Liquid NaK Alloy Confinement toward Stable Alkali-Metal Anodes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Cui, Junya; Jin, Bowen; Xu, Annan; Li, Jiale; Shao, Mingfei</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Advanced Science (Weinheim, Germany)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">10</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">8</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2206479</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ASDCCF</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2198-3844</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Room temp. liq. NaK alloy is a promising candidate for high performance metal batteries, due to its dendrite-free property and high energy d.  However, its practical application is hindered by the high surface tension of liq. NaK, which causes difficulties in maintaining a stable contact with a current collector.  Here, the authors demonstrate the extraordinary stable confinement of NaK alloy at room temp. by constructing a super-wetting substrate, which is based on highly dispersed cobalt-single-atom carbon nanoarrays.  The developed liq. anode electrode prevented successfully the leakage of NaK alloy even in harsh stress (&gt;5 MPa) or sharp shock conditions.  The sym. cells achieved ultra-long reversible plating/stripping cycling life in both Na-ion (&gt;1010 h) and K-ion electrolytes (&gt;4000 h) at 10 mA cm-2/10 mAh cm-2.  Upon fitting with Na3V2(PO4)3, the NaK assembled full battery provided high energy d. (332.6 kWh kg-1) and power d. (11.05 kW kg-1) with excellent stability after &gt;21600 cycles, which is the best value reported so far.  The prepd. pouch cell was able to drive a four-axis aircraft, demonstrating a great prospect in practical application.  This work offers a new approach in the prepn. of advanced dendrite-free liq. metal anodes with promising applications in electrochem. energy storage.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrHzgckebXGC7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0liimcxnVrZbyA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhsFyhtLc%253D&amp;md5=8ba44f47e50f7eb6b6fa59701a88d744</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref30"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref30'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">30</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit30" data-doi="10.1023/A:1022368403013"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shpil’rain, E.                         cas_cit30R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">30</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Experimental Investigation of the Activity of Sodium in a Liquid Sodium-Potassium Alloy in a Wide Temperature Range</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Shpil'rain, E.         </div><div class="casAbstract">The EMF method is applied to investigate the activity of sodium in a molten sodium-potassium alloy contg. 87.2 wt. % of potassium.  The measurements are performed in two different exptl. setups.  One of them uses glass contg. sodium ions as electrolyte, and the other one uses beta-ceramics.  Therefore, the limiting exptl. temp. in the first case does not exceed 550 K, while in the second case, it is about 750 K.  The maximal relative error of the exptl. data on the activity of sodium in a liq. Na-K alloy is approx. 3 %.  The discrepancy between the measurement results and the exptl. and theor. data available in the literature is within this error.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGo5KsZtx_kmeLVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0liimcxnVrZbyA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD3sXhtFSnsLk%253D&amp;md5=d03a9592f01f7169db205b8c10ea5c5c</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref31"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref31'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">31</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit31" data-doi="10.1002/aenm.202302046"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhu, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xiang, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Sun, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Tang, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, H.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Medium-Entropy Phosphate Cathode with Multielectron Redox Reaction for Advanced Sodium-Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Adv.                         cas_cit31R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">31</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A Medium-Entropy Phosphate Cathode with Multielectron Redox Reaction for Advanced Sodium-Ion Batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Zhu, Lin; Wang, Miaomiao; Xiang, Shuang; Sun, Dan; Tang, Yougen; Wang, Haiyan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Advanced Energy Materials</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">13</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">36</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2302046</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ADEMBC</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1614-6840</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-Blackwell</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Achieving multi-sodium storage and high operating voltage is key to boosting energy d. of NASICON-type materials.  However, the activation of more redox couples is usually accompanied by asym. and irreversible electrochem. reactions, thus causing fast capacity fading.  To address this issue, a medium-entropy concept is proposed, and a novel medium-entropy Na3Mn2/3V2/3Ti2/3(PO4)3/C@CNTs (ME-NMVTP) cathode is designed.  The as-prepd. ME-NMVTP achieves a successive redox reaction, delivering a highly reversible specific capacity of 147.9 mA h g-1 at 50 mA g-1 together with a long-term lifespan of 1000 cycles at 500 mA g-1 (capacity retention of 88.3%), which is superior to low-entropy cathodes such as Na4MnV(PO4)3/C@CNTs (LE-NMVP) and Na3MnTi(PO4)3/C@CNTs (LE-NMTP).  Moreover, benefiting from the entropy effect, solid-soln. and biphasic reactions with reversible structure evolution and small vol. change are achieved during the multi-sodium storage process.  First-principles calcn. and kinetic anal. results affirm the enhanced electronic cond. and facilitated Na+ migration of the ME-NMVTP cathode derived from the synergistic effect of the three transition-metal elementals in a medium-entropy cryst. state.  The strategy of engineering medium-entropy to construct cathodes with superior performance is expected to be widely applicable to other electrode materials.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGr8ptw8Ou3F7LVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgntfc6SEmObA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhslSmu7vM&amp;md5=6e5baf52bd3b5361fb7a938188a57b70</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref32"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref32'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">32</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit32" data-doi="10.1002/anie.202209458"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, L.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Monocrystalline Coordination Polymer with Multiple Redox Centers as a High-Performance Cathode for Lithium-Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Angew.                         cas_cit32R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">32</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A Monocrystalline Coordination Polymer with Multiple Redox Centers as a High-Performance Cathode for Lithium-Ion Batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Luo, Yuwen; Liu, Jinlong; Zhang, Lei</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Angewandte Chemie, International Edition</span>

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Coordination polymers can take advantage of both transition metal redox and org. ligand redox, thus serving as promising cathodes with multiple redox centers toward higher-performance lithium-ion batteries (LIBs).  Here, we selected the high-capacity carbonyl compd. of chloranilic acid (CA) as org. ligand to coordinate with the high-voltage Cu2+ as transition metal node and successfully synthesized copper(II) chloranilate (CuCA) with π-d conjugation, layered structure and monocryst. nature.  The resulting CuCA presents inorg. and org. redox centers, high electronic cond. and fast Li+ diffusion kinetics, leading to high discharge capacity (297.0 mAh g-1 at 50 mA g-1), excellent rate capability (160.6 mAh g-1 at 1000 mA g-1) and good cycling stability (165.5 mAh g-1 at 500 mA g-1 after 50 cycles) with quasi-solid-state electrolyte.  This work will provide insightful understanding of the materials design strategies to develop more efficient coordination polymer cathodes for LIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoF3cEfUX3zs7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgntfc6SEmObA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB38XitFKjsrvF&amp;md5=2400a0f5781eabf15737c04b0658665d</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref33"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref33'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">33</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit33" data-doi="10.1021/jacs.7b12267"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, L.                         cas_cit33R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">33</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Cathode Dependence of Liquid-Alloy Na-K Anodes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Xue, Leigang; Gao, Hongcai; Li, Yutao; Goodenough, John B.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of the American Chemical Society</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2018</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">140</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">9</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">3292-3298</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JACSAT</span>;

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Alkali ions can be plated dendrite-free into a liq. alkali-metal anode.  Commercialized Na-S battery technol. operates above 300 °C.  A low-cost Na-K alloy is liq. at 25 °C from 9.2 to 58.2 wt% of sodium; sodium and/or potassium can be plated dendrite-free in the liq. range at room temp.  The co-existence of two alkali metals in an anode raises a question: whether the liq. Na-K alloy acts as a Na or a K anode.  Here we show the alkali-metal that is stripped from the liq. Na-K anode is dependent on the preference of the cathode host.  It acts as the anode of a sodium rechargeable cell if the cathode host structure selectively accepts only Na+ ions; as the anode of a potassium rechargeable cell if the cathode accepts K+ ions in preference to Na+ ions.  This dual-anode behavior means the liq. Na-K alkali-alloy can be applied as a dendrite-free anode in Na-metal batteries as well as K-metal batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoIA6YqZC7AtbVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgntfc6SEmObA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXisF2hurw%253D&amp;md5=e1a58635942372cb78d7410b4c070e58</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref34"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref34'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">34</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit34" data-doi="10.1016/j.jpowsour.2008.12.047"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chan, C. A.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Cui, Y.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Structural and Electrochemical Study of the Reaction of Lithium with Silicon Nanowires</span>. <i>J.                         cas_cit34R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">34</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Structural and electrochemical study of the reaction of lithium with silicon nanowires</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Chan, Candace K.; Ruffo, Riccardo; Hong, Seung Sae; Huggins, Robert A.; Cui, Yi</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Power Sources</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2009</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">189</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">1</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">34-39</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JPSODZ</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0378-7753</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier B.V.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The structural transformations of silicon nanowires when cycled against lithium were evaluated using electrochem. potential spectroscopy and galvanostatic cycling.  During the charge, the nanowires alloy with lithium to form an amorphous LixSi compd.  At potentials &lt;50 mV, a structural transformation occurs.  In studies on micron-sized particles previously reported in the literature, this transformation is a crystn. to a metastable Li15Si4 phase.  X-ray diffraction measurements on the Si nanowires, however, show that they are amorphous, suggesting that a different amorphous phase (LiySi) is formed.  Lithium is removed from this phase in the discharge to form amorphous silicon.  We have found that limiting the voltage in the charge to 70 mV results in improved efficiency and cyclability compared to charging to 10 mV.  This improvement is due to the suppression of the transformation at low potentials, which alloys for reversible cycling of amorphous silicon nanowires.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpsCFHr4yV8M7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgntfc6SEmObA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD1MXjsVehu7Y%253D&amp;md5=b2a7eb47c0357e0d47b46d6b51c66a4d</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref35"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref35'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">35</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit35" data-doi="10.1016/j.nanoen.2019.103881"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Hou, T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yang, G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Rajput, N. A.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">The Influence of FEC on the Solvation Structure and Reduction Reaction of LiPF<sub>6</sub>/EC Electrolytes and its Implication for Solid Electrolyte Interphase Formation</span>. <i>Nano Energy</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>64</i></span>, <span class="NLM_elocation-id">103881</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1016/j.nanoen.2019.103881</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D64%26publication_year%3D2019%26journal%3DNano%2BEnergy%26author%3DT.%2BHou%26author%3DG.%2BYang%26author%3DN.%2BN.%2BRajput%26author%3DJ.%2BSelf%26author%3DS.-W.%2BPark%26author%3DJ.%2BNanda%26author%3DK.%2BA.%2BPersson%26title%3DThe%2BInfluence%2Bof%2BFEC%2Bon%2Bthe%2BSolvation%2BStructure%2Band%2BReduction%2BReaction%2Bof%2BLiPF6%252FEC%2BElectrolytes%2Band%2Bits%2BImplication%2Bfor%2BSolid%2BElectrolyte%2BInterphase%2BFormation%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.nanoen.2019.103881&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.nanoen.2019.103881&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit35R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">35</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">The influence of FEC on the solvation structure and reduction reaction of LiPF6/EC electrolytes and its implication for solid electrolyte interphase formation</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Hou, Tingzheng; Yang, Guang; Rajput, Nav Nidhi; Self, Julian; Park, Sang-Won; Nanda, Jagjit; Persson, Kristin A.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nano Energy</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">64</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">103881</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">NEANCA</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2211-2855</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier Ltd.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) has been proposed as an effective electrolyte additive that enhances the stability and elasticity of the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) of emerging Si and Li metal anodes.  However, uncertainties still remain on the exact mechanism through which FEC alters the electrolyte decompn. and SEI formation process.  Herein, the influence of FEC on LiPF6/ethylene carbonate (EC) electrolytes for Si anodes is investigated through classical mol. dynamics, Fourier-transform IR spectroscopy, and quantum chem. calcns.  Albeit a minority species, FEC is found to significantly modify the solvation structure and redn. behavior of the electrolyte while being innocuous to transport properties.  Even with limited 10% of FEC, the Li+ solvation structure exhibits a notably higher contact-ion pair ratio (14%) than the parent EC electrolyte (6%).  Moreover, FEC itself, as a new fluorine-contg. species, appears in 1/5 of the Li+ solvation shells.  The Li+-coordinated FEC is found to reduce prior to EC and uncoordinated FEC which will passivate the anode surface at an early onset (ca. 0.3 V higher than EC) by forming LiF.  The crit. role of FEC in tailoring the Li+ solvation structure and as-formed protective SEI compn. provides mechanistic insight that will aid in the rational design of novel electrolytes.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpRXCDK39nHp7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgntfc6SEmObA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1MXhsVais73K&amp;md5=9ddf9385a4e89de8a93b9e17baadfa10</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref36"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref36'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">36</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit36" data-doi="10.1016/j.electacta.2015.09.097"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wan, T. H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Saccoccio, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chen, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ciucci, F.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Influence of the Discretization Methods on the Distribution of Relaxation Times Deconvolution: Implementing Radial Basis Functions with DRTtools</span>. <i>Electrochim. Acta</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2015</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>184</i></span>,  <span class="NLM_fpage">483</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">499</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1016/j.electacta.2015.09.097</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D184%26publication_year%3D2015%26pages%3D483-499%26journal%3DElectrochim.%2BActa%26author%3DT.%2BH.%2BWan%26author%3DM.%2BSaccoccio%26author%3DC.%2BChen%26author%3DF.%2BCiucci%26title%3DInfluence%2Bof%2Bthe%2BDiscretization%2BMethods%2Bon%2Bthe%2BDistribution%2Bof%2BRelaxation%2BTimes%2BDeconvolution%253A%2BImplementing%2BRadial%2BBasis%2BFunctions%2Bwith%2BDRTtools%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.electacta.2015.09.097&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.electacta.2015.09.097&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit36R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">36</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Influence of the Discretization Methods on the Distribution of Relaxation Times Deconvolution: Implementing Radial Basis Functions with DRTtools</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Wan, Ting Hei; Saccoccio, Mattia; Chen, Chi; Ciucci, Francesco</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Electrochimica Acta</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2015</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">184</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">483-499</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ELCAAV</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0013-4686</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier Ltd.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The distribution of relaxation times (DRT) is an approach that can ext. time characteristics of an electrochem. system from electrochem. impedance spectroscopy (EIS) measurements.  Computing the DRT is difficult because it is an intrinsically ill-posed problem often requiring regularization.  To improve the estn. of the DRT and to better control its error, a suitable discretization basis for the regularized regression needs to be chosen.  However, this aspect was invariably overlooked in the specialized literature.  Pseudo-spectral methods using radial basis functions (RBFs) are, in principle, a better choice in comparison to other discretization basis, such as piecewise linear (PWL) functions, because they may achieve fast convergence.  Also, they can yield improved estn. by extending the estd. DRT to the entire frequency spectrum, if the underlying DRT decays to zero sufficiently fast outside the measured frequency range.  Addnl., their implementation is relatively easier than other types of pseudo-spectral methods since they do not require ad hoc collocation point distributions.  The as-developed novel RBF-based DRT framework was tested against controlled synthetic EIS spectra and real exptl. data.  The authors' results indicate that the RBF discretization performance is comparable with that of the PWL discretization at normal data collection range, and with improvement when the EIS acquisition is incomplete.  Also applying RBF discretization for deconvolving the DRT problem can lead to faster numerical convergence rate as compared with that of PWL discretization only at error free situation.  As a companion to this work the authors have developed a MATLAB GUI toolbox, which can be used to solve DRT regularization problems.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpYy-prOe07w7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljrTUhfEwDCbA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2MXhvVehurjJ&amp;md5=d8084e5c872949719e4937f608b428ce</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref37"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref37'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">37</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit37" data-doi="10.1016/j.ensm.2022.06.016"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Soni, R.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Robinson, J. B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shearing, P. R.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Brett, D. J.                 10.1016/j.ensm.2022.06.016</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D51%26publication_year%3D2022%26pages%3D97-107%26journal%3DEnergy%2BStorage%2BMater.%26author%3DR.%2BSoni%26author%3DJ.%2BB.%2BRobinson%26author%3DP.%2BR.%2BShearing%26author%3DD.%2BJ.%2BL.%2BBrett%26author%3DA.%2BJ.%2BE.%2BRettie%26author%3DT.%2BS.%2BMiller%26title%3DLithium-Sulfur%2BBattery%2BDiagnostics%2BThrough%2BDistribution%2Bof%2BRelaxation%2BTimes%2BAnalysis%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.ensm.2022.06.016&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.ensm.2022.06.016&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord empty" id="
                            cas_R
                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref38"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref38'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">38</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit38" data-doi="10.1016/j.surfin.2020.100911"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhuo, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ma, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yan, G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Tan, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mai, W.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Improving Rechargeability of Prussian blue Cathode by Graphene as Conductive Agent for Sodium Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Surf.                 10.1016/j.surfin.2020.100911</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D23%26publication_year%3D2021%26journal%3DSurf.%2BInterfaces%26author%3DW.%2BZhuo%26author%3DJ.%2BLi%26author%3DX.%2BLi%26author%3DL.%2BMa%26author%3DG.%2BYan%26author%3DH.%2BWang%26author%3DS.%2BTan%26author%3DW.%2BMai%26title%3DImproving%2BRechargeability%2Bof%2BPrussian%2Bblue%2BCathode%2Bby%2BGraphene%2Bas%2BConductive%2BAgent%2Bfor%2BSodium%2BIon%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.surfin.2020.100911&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.surfin.2020.100911&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit38R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">38</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Improving rechargeability of Prussian blue cathode by graphene as conductive agent for sodium ion batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Zhuo, Wenchen; Li, Jinliang; Li, Xiaodan; Ma, Liang; Yan, Genghua; Wang, Hao; Tan, Shaozao; Mai, Wenjie</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Surfaces and Interfaces</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2021</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">23</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">100911</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">SIUNCN</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2468-0230</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier B.V.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium ion batteries (NIBs) have gradually become an alternative to lithium ion batteries.  Prussian blues (PBs) are regarded as a promising kind of cathode materials for NIBs, but their poor elec. cond. has always been a considerable issue limiting its performance.  In our work, we have optimized the PB cathode by utilizing reduced graphene oxide (RGO) as the conductive additive, whose performance is much higher than that of PB cathode with conventional conductive Super P.  After optimization, our PB cathode with RGO additive delivers a reversible specific capacity of 80 mAh g-1 at 50 mA g-1 after 200 cycles without obvious attenuation.  We also adopt current images and distribution of relaxation time technol. to further analyze the reasons of electrochem. performance improvement.  It is found that RGO conductive additive can remarkably enhance the intensity and uniformity of current in the electrode.  We believe our work will provide new insights into the field of NIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrJo2Pif9AT37Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljrTUhfEwDCbA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3MXht1ahs7zL&amp;md5=7e2b12f38268e933c0d82dd968dd5066</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref39"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref39'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">39</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit39" data-doi="10.1016/j.jpowsour.2012.07.100"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Schmidt, J.                 10.1016/j.jpowsour.2012.07.100</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D221%26publication_year%3D2013%26pages%3D70-77%26journal%3DJ.%2BPower%2BSources%26author%3DJ.%2BP.%2BSchmidt%26author%3DP.%2BBerg%26author%3DM.%2BSch%25C3%25B6nleber%26author%3DA.%2BWeber%26author%3DE.%2BIvers-Tiff%25C3%25A9e%26title%3DThe%2BDistribution%2Bof%2BRelaxation%2BTimes%2Bas%2BBasis%2Bfor%2BGeneralized%2BTime-Domain%2BModels%2Bfor%2BLi-ion%2BBatteries%26doi%3D10.1016%252Fj.jpowsour.2012.07.100&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1016%2Fj.jpowsour.2012.07.100&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit39R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">39</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">The distribution of relaxation times as basis for generalized time-domain models for Li-ion batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Schmidt, Jan Philipp; Berg, Philipp; Schoenleber, Michael; Weber, Andre; Ivers-Tiffee, Ellen</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Power Sources</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2013</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">221</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">70-77</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JPSODZ</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0378-7753</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier B.V.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A novel approach for the development of a model for Li-ion batteries with the potential for application in on-board diagnostic is introduced.  This approach is not tied to a particular electrochem., and has the advantages of scalability and automatable parameterization as well as feasibility regarding an implementation on microcontrollers.  The dynamic behavior of the cell under test, a Li-ion pouch cell with a graphite anode and a blend cathode, is characterized in an extremely broad frequency range from 100 kHz to 17 μHz.  The introduced model gives predictions consistent with the exptl. data, its accuracy depends on the assumed no. of relaxation times resp. model order.  Recommendations concerning application are given and limitations of the approach are discussed.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpKxmbmW_kelrVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljrTUhfEwDCbA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC38XhsVGjsrfJ&amp;md5=906370a6a349f07d83af51237db0ada0</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref40"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref40'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">40</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit40" data-doi="10.1021/acsami.6b05075"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ivanova, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhecheva, E.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Kukeva, R.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Nihtianova, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mihaylov, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Atanasova, G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Stoyanova, R.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Layered P3-Na<sub>x</sub>Co<sub>1/3</sub>Ni<sub>1/3</sub>Mn<sub>1/3</sub>O<sub>2</sub> versus Spinel Li<sub>4</sub>Ti<sub>5</sub>O<sub>12</sub> as a Positive and a Negative Electrode in a Full Sodium–Lithium Cell</span>. <i>ACS Appl. Mater. Interfaces.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2016</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>8</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">27</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">17321</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">17333</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acsami.6b05075</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D8%26publication_year%3D2016%26pages%3D17321-17333%26journal%3DACS%2BAppl.%2BMater.%2BInterfaces.%26issue%3D27%26author%3DS.%2BIvanova%26author%3DE.%2BZhecheva%26author%3DR.%2BKukeva%26author%3DD.%2BNihtianova%26author%3DL.%2BMihaylov%26author%3DG.%2BAtanasova%26author%3DR.%2BStoyanova%26title%3DLayered%2BP3-NaxCo1%252F3Ni1%252F3Mn1%252F3O2%2Bversus%2BSpinel%2BLi4Ti5O12%2Bas%2Ba%2BPositive%2Band%2Ba%2BNegative%2BElectrode%2Bin%2Ba%2BFull%2BSodium%25E2%2580%2593Lithium%2BCell%26doi%3D10.1021%252Facsami.6b05075&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1021%2Facsami.6b05075&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit40R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">40</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Layered P3-NaxCo1/3Ni1/3Mn1/3O2 versus Spinel Li4Ti5O12 as a Positive and a Negative Electrode in a Full Sodium-Lithium Cell</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Ivanova, Svetlana; Zhecheva, Ekaterina; Kukeva, Rositsa; Nihtianova, Diana; Mihaylov, Lyuben; Atanasova, Genoveva; Stoyanova, Radostina</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">ACS Applied Materials &amp; Interfaces</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2016</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">8</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">27</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">17321-17333</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">AAMICK</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1944-8244</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The development of lithium and sodium ion batteries without using lithium and sodium metal as anodes gives the impetus for elaboration of low-cost and environmentally friendly energy storage devices.  In this contribution we demonstrate the design and construction of a new type of hybrid sodium-lithium ion cell by using unique electrode combination (Li4Ti5O12 spinel as a neg. electrode and layered Na3/4Co1/3Ni1/3Mn1/3O2 as a pos. electrode) and conventional lithium electrolyte (LiPF6 salt dissolved in EC/DMC).  The cell operates at an av. potential of 2.35 V by delivering a reversible capacity of about 100 mAh/g.  The mechanism of the electrochem. reaction in the full sodium-lithium ion cell is studied by means of postmortem anal., as well as ex situ X-ray diffraction anal., HR-TEM, and ESR spectroscopy (EPR).  The changes in the surface compn. of electrodes are examd. by ex situ XPS.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrAB_lR7TLQtrVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljrTUhfEwDCbA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC28XpvFyktrs%253D&amp;md5=327a551db67ea69a0787e2e270d6255f</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref41"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref41'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">41</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit41" data-doi="10.1016/j.jnoncrysol.2010.09.031"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Nesbitt, H.                         cas_cit42R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">42</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">SEI composition on hard carbon in Na-Ion batteries after long cycling: Influence of salts (NaPF6, NaTFSI) and Additives (FEC, DMCF)</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Fondard, J.; Irisarri, E.; Courreges, C.; Palacin, M. R.; Ponrouch, A.; Dedryvere, R.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of the Electrochemical Society</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2020</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">167</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">7</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">070526</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JESOAN</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0013-4651</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Electrochemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A study of the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) on hard-carbon (HC) electrodes in sodium half-cells is presented.  Electrochem. performances over &gt; 100 cycles were compared with two different salts (NaPF6, NaTFSI) and two different electrolyte additives (FEC, DMCF) in a mixt. of EC and DMC solvents.  The best electrochem. performances were obsd. with NaPF6 salt in conjunction with 3% FEC.  The DMCF additive had a detrimental effect in all electrolyte combinations.  The chem. characterization of the SEI was carried out by XPS and showed that the best electrochem. behavior was related to an SEI compn. based on sodium ethylene dicarbonate and NaF, whereas poorer electrochem. performances were assocd. to either low NaF or high Na2CO3 content.  The results reported herein provide an insight on the SEI chem. on hard carbon electrodes in sodium cells after long-term cycling, as a complement to previous studies dealing with the first cycles.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGq4rxL0JhE-c7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljrTUhfEwDCbA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3cXosVKisL0%253D&amp;md5=fc871aceb661bd6af19f8153b66817bd</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref43"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref43'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">43</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit43" data-doi="10.1002/adfm.202214195"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhu, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wu, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Guo, K.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, Q.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ma, J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Optimizing NaF-Rich Solid Electrolyte Interphase for Stabilizing Sodium Metal Batteries by Electrolyte Additive</span>. <i>Adv.                 10.1039/C7CC09751D</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D54%26publication_year%3D2018%26pages%3D2381-2384%26journal%3DChem.%2BCommun.%26issue%3D19%26author%3DM.%2BHan%26author%3DC.%2BZhu%26author%3DT.%2BMa%26author%3DZ.%2BPan%26author%3DZ.%2BTao%26author%3DJ.%2BChen%26title%3DIn%2Bsitu%2BAtomic%2BForce%2BMicroscopy%2BStudy%2Bof%2BNano%25E2%2580%2593Micro%2BSodium%2BDeposition%2Bin%2BEster-Based%2BElectrolytes%26doi%3D10.1039%252FC7CC09751D&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1039%2FC7CC09751D&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit44R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">44</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">In situ atomic force microscopy study of nano-micro sodium deposition in ester-based electrolytes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Han, Mo; Zhu, Chenbo; Ma, Ting; Pan, Zeng; Tao, Zhanliang; Chen, Jun</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Communications (Cambridge, United Kingdom)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2018</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">54</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">19</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2381-2384</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CHCOFS</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1359-7345</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">We report an in situ anal. of nano-micro sodium deposition in an ester-based electrolyte using at. force microscopy.  It is found that sodium dendrites are effectively suppressed by adding fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) as an electrolyte additive.  The decompn. of FEC provides a NaF-contg. solid electrolyte interphase with homogenous morphol. and high modulus, leading to stable sodium deposition and high Coulombic efficiency (88% over 50 cycles) of the sodium metal anode.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGq5pWPIj3u8PbVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgb5h8N61K0lQ"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXis1Sjs70%253D&amp;md5=319a4271168dc251c114f0d972e6048e</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="ref45"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="showRef(event, 'ref45'); return false;" data-citation="" class="refNumLink">45</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="cit45" data-doi="10.1002/smll.202304162"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yi, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhong, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yan, G.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Uncovering the Redox Shuttle Degradation Mechanism of Ether Electrolytes in Sodium-Ion Batteries and its Inhibition Strategy</span>. <i>Small</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2023</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>19</i></span>, <span class="NLM_elocation-id">2304162</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/smll.202304162</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><span class="references__suffix"><a class="google-scholar" href="/action/getFTRLinkout?url=http%3A%2F%2Fscholar.google.com%2Fscholar_lookup%3Fhl%3Den%26volume%3D19%26publication_year%3D2023%26journal%3DSmall%26author%3DX.%2BYi%26author%3DX.%2BLi%26author%3DJ.%2BZhong%26author%3DZ.%2BWang%26author%3DH.%2BGuo%26author%3DW.%2BPeng%26author%3DJ.%2BDuan%26author%3DD.%2BWang%26author%3DJ.%2BWang%26author%3DG.%2BYan%26title%3DUncovering%2Bthe%2BRedox%2BShuttle%2BDegradation%2BMechanism%2Bof%2BEther%2BElectrolytes%2Bin%2BSodium-Ion%2BBatteries%2Band%2Bits%2BInhibition%2BStrategy%26doi%3D10.1002%252Fsmll.202304162&amp;doi=10.1021%2Facsami.3c15338&amp;doiOfLink=10.1002%2Fsmll.202304162&amp;linkType=gs&amp;linkLocation=Reference&amp;linkSource=FULL_TEXT" target="_blank">Google Scholar</a></span><div class="casRecord" id="
                        cas_cit45R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">45</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Uncovering the Redox Shuttle Degradation Mechanism of Ether Electrolytes in Sodium-Ion Batteries and its Inhibition Strategy</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Yi, Xiaoli; Li, Xinhai; Zhong, Jing; Wang, Zhixing; Guo, Huajun; Peng, Wenjie; Duan, Jianguo; Wang, Ding; Wang, Jiexi; Yan, Guochun</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Small</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">19</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">52</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2304162</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">SMALBC</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1613-6810</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Ether-based electrolytes exhibit excellent performance when applied in different anode materials of sodium ion batteries (SIBs), but their exploration on cathode material is deficient and the degrdn. mechanism is still undiscovered.  Herein, various battery systems with different operation voltage ranges are designed to explore the electrochem. performance of ether electrolyte.  It is found for the first time that the deterioration mechanism of ether electrolyte is closely related to the "redox shuttle" between cathode and low-potential anode.  The "shuttle" is discovered to occur when the potential of anodes is below 0.57 V, and the gas products coming from "shuttle" intermediates are revealed by differential electrochem. mass spectrometry (DEMS).  Moreover, effective inhibition strategies by protecting low-potential anodes are proposed and verified; ethylene carbonate (EC) is found to be very effective as an additive by forming an inorgs.-rich solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) on low-potential anodes, thereby suppressing the deterioration of ether electrolytes.  This work reveals the failure mechanism of ether-based electrolytes applied in SIBs and proposes effective strategies to suppress the "shuttle," which provides a valuable guidance for advancing the application of ether-based electrolytes in SIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrHtW-bcsxZfLVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgb5h8N61K0lQ"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhvVWrtrnI&amp;md5=bbc1bea2c79d35e6664414912e296820</span></div></div></div></div></li></ol></div><script type="text/javascript" nonce="90f6e6353ec9775c-SJC">window.refViewer={'ref1':['cit1'],'ref2':['cit2'],'ref3':['cit3'],'ref4':['cit4'],'ref5':['cit5'],'ref6':['cit6'],'ref7':['cit7'],'ref8':['cit8'],'ref9':['cit9'],'ref10':['cit10'],'ref11':['cit11'],'ref12':['cit12'],'ref13':['cit13'],'ref14':['cit14'],'ref15':['cit15'],'ref16':['cit16'],'ref17':['cit17'],'ref18':['cit18'],'ref19':['cit19'],'ref20':['cit20'],'ref21':['cit21'],'ref22':['cit22'],'ref23':['cit23'],'ref24':['cit24'],'ref25':['cit25'],'ref26':['cit26'],'ref27':['cit27'],'ref28':['cit28'],'ref29':['cit29'],'ref30':['cit30'],'ref31':['cit31'],'ref32':['cit32'],'ref33':['cit33'],'ref34':['cit34'],'ref35':['cit35'],'ref36':['cit36'],'ref37':['cit37'],'ref38':['cit38'],'ref39':['cit39'],'ref40':['cit40'],'ref41':['cit41'],'ref42':['cit42'],'ref43':['cit43'],'ref44':['cit44'],'ref45':['cit45']}</script><div class="articleCitedByDropzone" data-pb-dropzone="articleCitedByDropzone"><div class="cited-by"><div class="article_content-header cited-content_header"><div class="article_content-header-row"><div tabindex="0" class="article_content-title"><h2 id="citeThis">Cited By</h2><div class="article__copy"> <button class="article__copy__btn"><i aria-hidden="true" class="article__copy__icon icon-copy-solid"></i></button><span class="article__copy__text">Click to copy section link</span><span class="article__copy__success">Section link copied!</span></div></div></div></div><div class="cited-by__content"><div class="sciteMetricsDropzone">

class="article__inlineFigure"><h2 class="fig-label">Abstract</h2><a class="internalNav" aria-label="scroll to figure" href="#_i1"><img class="rightTab-fig internalNav" src="/cms/10.1021/acsami.3c15338/asset/images/medium/am3c15338_0006.gif" alt="" id="rightTab-tgr1"></a><div class="figure-bottom-links"><div class="download-hi-res-img"><a title="High Resolution href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1021/acsami.3c15338&amp;id=_i1"><span>Download MS PowerPoint Slide</span></a></div></div></figure><figure data-id="fig1" data-index="1" class="article__inlineFigure"><h2 class="fig-label">Figure 1</h2><a class="internalNav" aria-label="scroll to figure" href="#fig1"><img src="/cms/10.1021/acsami.3c15338/asset/images/medium/am3c15338_0001.gif" alt="" data-lg-src="/cms/10.1021/acsami.3c15338/asset/images/large/am3c15338_0001.jpeg" id="rightTab-gr1" class="rightTab-fig internalNav"></a><figcaption><div class="hlFld-FigureCaption caption"><p class="first last">Figure 1. (a, b) Cycling curves and stability of NaK anode in a 1:1 ratio of 1 M NaPF<sub>6</sub>:KPF<sub>6</sub> electrolyte, with 5% FEC at 1C. Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2009</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>8</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">4</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">320</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">324</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1038/nmat2418</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit3R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">3</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">High-energy cathode material for long-life and safe lithium batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Sun, Yang-Kook; Myung, Seung-Taek; Park, Byung-Chun; Prakash, Jai; Belharouak, Ilias; Amine, Khalil</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nature Materials</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2009</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">8</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">4</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">320-324</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">NMAACR</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1476-1122</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Nature Publishing Group</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Layered lithium nickel-rich oxides, Li[Ni1-xMx]O2 (M = metal), have attracted significant interest as the cathode material for rechargeable lithium batteries owing to their high capacity, excellent rate capability and low cost.  However, their low thermal-abuse tolerance and poor cycle life, esp. at elevated temp., prohibit their use in practical batteries.  Here, we report on a concn.-gradient cathode material for rechargeable lithium batteries based on a layered lithium nickel cobalt manganese oxide.  In this material, each particle has a central bulk that is rich in Ni and a Mn-rich outer layer with decreasing Ni concn. and increasing Mn and Co concns. as the surface is approached.  The former provides high capacity, whereas the latter improves the thermal stability.  A half cell using our concn.-gradient cathode material achieved a high capacity of 209 mA-h/g and retained 96% of this capacity after 50 charge-discharge cycles under an aggressive test profile (55° between 3.0 and 4.4 V).  Our concn.-gradient material also showed superior performance in thermal-abuse tests compared with the bulk compn. Li[Ni0.8Co0.1Mn0.1]O2 used as ref.  These results suggest that our cathode material could enable prodn. of batteries that meet the demanding performance and safety requirements of plug-in hybrid elec. vehicles.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpdj6x9OC-KubVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhk-u41EYMwiA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD1MXjsFKntrw%253D&amp;md5=a3d00f1540a4bfff34846f105ea2d54d</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref4"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref4" class="rightTabRefNumLink">4</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit4" data-doi="10.1002/adma.201705575"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shi, J.-L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xiao, D.-D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ge, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yu, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chu, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Huang, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.-D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gu, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wan, L.-J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">High-Capacity Cathode Material with High Voltage for Li-Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Adv. Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2018</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>30</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">9</span>), <span class="NLM_elocation-id">1705575</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/adma.201705575</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord empty" id="

                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref5"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref5" class="rightTabRefNumLink">5</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit5" data-doi="10.1039/C4EE03029J"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Dunn, J. B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gaines, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Kelly, J. C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">James, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gallagher, K. G.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">The Significance of Li-ion Batteries in Electric Vehicle Life-Cycle Energy and Emissions and Recycling’s Role in its Reduction</span>. <i>Energy Environ. Sci.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2015</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>8</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">1</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">158</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">168</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1039/C4EE03029J</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit5R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">5</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">The significance of Li-ion batteries in electric vehicle life-cycle energy and emissions and recycling's role in its reduction</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Dunn, J. B.; Gaines, L.; Kelly, J. C.; James, C.; Gallagher, K. G.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Energy &amp; Environmental Science</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2015</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">8</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">1</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">158-168</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">EESNBY</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1754-5706</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Three key questions have driven recent discussions of the energy and environmental impacts of automotive lithium-ion batteries.  We address each of them, beginning with whether the energy intensity of producing all materials used in batteries or that of battery assembly is greater.  Notably, battery assembly energy intensity depends on assembly facility throughput because energy consumption of equipment, esp. the dry room, is mainly throughput-independent.  Low-throughput facilities therefore will have higher energy intensities than near-capacity facilities.  In our anal., adopting an assembly energy intensity reflective of a low-throughput plant caused the assembly stage to dominate cradle-to-gate battery energy and environmental impact results.  Results generated with an at-capacity assembly plant energy intensity, however, indicated cathode material prodn. and aluminum use as a structural material were the drivers.  Ests. of cradle-to-gate battery energy and environmental impacts must therefore be interpreted in light of assumptions made about assembly facility throughput.  The second key question is whether battery recycling is worthwhile if battery assembly dominates battery cradle-to-gate impacts.  In this case, even if recycled cathode materials are less energy and emissions intensive than virgin cathode materials, little energy and environmental benefit is obtained from their use because the energy consumed in assembly is so high.  We reviewed the local impacts of metals recovery for cathode materials and concluded that avoiding or reducing these impacts, including SOx emissions and water contamination, is a key motivator of battery recycling regardless of the energy intensity of assembly.  Finally, we address whether elec. vehicles (EV) offer improved energy and environmental performance compared to internal combustion-engine vehicles (ICV).  This anal. illustrated that, even if a battery assembly energy reflective of a low-throughput facility is adopted, EVs consume less petroleum and emit fewer greenhouse gases (GHG) than an ICV on a life-cycle basis.  The only scenario in which an EV emitted more GHGs than an ICV was when it used solely coal-derived electricity as a fuel source.  SOx emissions, however, were up to four times greater for EVs than ICVs.  These emissions could be reduced through battery recycling.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGret76te8bENrVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhk-u41EYMwiA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2cXhvV2mtL3P&amp;md5=4dc88d7068d183d656e2ec3314cc9e58</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref6"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref6" class="rightTabRefNumLink">6</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit6" data-doi="10.1016/j.ensm.2021.02.032"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Costa, C. J.         </div><div class="casAbstract">A review.  Li-ion battery commercialized by Sony in 1991 has the highest energy-d. among practical rechargeable batteries and is widely used in electronic devices, elec. vehicles, and stationary energy storage system in the world.  Moreover, the battery market is rapidly growing in the world and further fast-growing is expected.  With expansion of the demand and applications, price of lithium and cobalt resources is increasing.  We are, therefore, motivated to study Na- and K-ion batteries for stationary energy storage system because of much abundant Na and K resources and the wide distribution in the world.  In this account, we review developments of Na- and K-ion batteries with mainly introducing our previous and present researches in comparison to that of Li-ion battery.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoSYlvjIhnmwLVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljasF3Ean4Y2g"> &gt;&gt;                         rightTab-cas_cit11R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">11</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Tuning crystal structure and redox potential of NASICON-type cathodes for sodium-ion batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Ma, Xuemei; Cao, Xinxin; Zhou, Yifan; Guo, Shan; Shi, Xiaodong; Fang, Guozhao; Pan, Anqiang; Lu, Bingan; Zhou, Jiang; Liang, Shuquan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nano Research</span>

        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium superionic conductor (NASICON)-type compds. have been regarded as promising cathodes for sodium-ion batteries (SIBs) due to their favorable ionic cond. and robust structural stability.  However, their high cost and relatively low energy d. restrict their further practical application, which can be tailored by widening the operating voltages with earth-abundant elements such as Mn.  Here, we propose a rational strategy of infusing Mn element in NASICON frameworks with sufficiently mobile sodium ions that enhances the redox voltage and ionic migration activity.  The optimized structure of Na3.5Mn0.5V1.5(PO4)3/C is achieved and investigated systematically to be a durable cathode (76.6% capacity retention over 5,000 cycles at 20 C) for SIBs, which exhibits high reversible capacity (113.1 mAh·g-1 at 0.5 C) with relatively low vol. change (7.6%).  Importantly, its high-areal-loading and temp.-resistant sodium ion storage properties are evaluated, and the full-cell configuration is demonstrated.  This work indicates that this Na3.5Mn0.5V1.5(PO4)3/C composite could be a promising cathode candidate for SIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrjespGri5z6bVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljasF3Ean4Y2g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3cXitVWrs7jM&amp;md5=0b5cc8fe989d085f223643702c692210</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref12"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref12" class="rightTabRefNumLink">12</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit12" data-doi="10.1146/annurev-physchem-040513-103644"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wyttenbach, T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Pierson, N.         </div><div class="casAbstract">A review.  The combination of mass spectrometry and ion mobility spectrometry (IMS) employing a temp.-variable drift cell or a drift tube divided into sections to make IMS-IMS expts. possible allows information to be obtained about the mol. dynamics of polyat. ions in the absence of a solvent.  The expts. allow the investigation of structural changes of both activated and native ion populations on a timescale of 1-100 ms.  Five different systems representing small and large, polar and nonpolar mols., as well as noncovalent assemblies, are discussed in detail: a dinucleotide, a sodiated polyethylene glycol chain, the peptide bradykinin, the protein ubiquitin, and two types of peptide oligomers.  Barriers to conformational interconversion can be obtained in favorable cases.  In other cases, soln.-like native structures can be obsd., but care must be taken in the exptl. protocols.  The power of theor. modeling is demonstrated.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGodqjrP5GsbR7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljasF3Ean4Y2g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2cXhtVKjtLvO&amp;md5=a5f03a8a245e3c361571bfb103adf391</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref13"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref13" class="rightTabRefNumLink">13</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit13" data-doi="10.1039/C7CC00301C"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jian, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Rodríguez-Pérez, I.         </div><div class="casAbstract">The rate capability of hard carbon has long been underestimated in prior studies that used carbon/Na two-electrode half-cells.
