Chem. Res.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2016</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>49</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">2</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">231</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">240</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acs.accounts.5b00482</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit14R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">14</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Na-Ion Battery Anodes: Materials and Electrochemistry</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Luo, Wei; Shen, Fei; Bommier, Clement; Zhu, Hongli; Ji, Xiulei; Hu, Liangbing</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Accounts of Chemical Research</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2016</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">49</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">2</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">231-240</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ACHRE4</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0001-4842</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The intermittent nature of renewable energy sources, such as solar and wind, calls for sustainable elec. energy storage (EES) technologies for stationary applications.  Li will be simply too rare for Li-ion batteries (LIBs) to be used for large-scale storage purposes.  In contrast, Na-ion batteries (NIBs) are highly promising to meet the demand of grid-level storage because Na is truly earth abundant and ubiquitous around the globe.  Furthermore, NIBs share a similar rocking-chair operation mechanism with LIBs, which potentially provides high reversibility and long cycling life.  It would be most efficient to transfer knowledge learned on LIBs during the last three decades to the development of NIBs.  Following this logic, rapid progress has been made in NIB cathode materials, where layered metal oxides and polyanionic compds. exhibit encouraging results.  On the anode side, pure graphite as the std. anode for LIBs can only form NaC64 in NIBs if solvent co-intercalation does not occur due to the unfavorable thermodn.  In fact, it was the utilization of a carbon anode in LIBs that enabled the com. successes.  Anodes of metal-ion batteries det. key characteristics, such as safety and cycling life; thus, it is indispensable to identify suitable anode materials for NIBs.In this Account, we review recent development on anode materials for NIBs.  Due to the limited space, we will mainly discuss carbon-based and alloy-based anodes and highlight progress made in our groups in this field.  We first present what is known about the failure mechanism of graphite anode in NIBs.  We then go on to discuss studies on hard carbon anodes, alloy-type anodes, and org. anodes.  Esp., the multiple functions of natural cellulose that is used as a low-cost carbon precursor for mass prodn. and as a soft substrate for tin anodes are highlighted.  The strategies of minimizing the surface area of carbon anodes for improving the first-cycle Coulombic efficiency are also outlined, where graphene oxide was employed as dehydration agent and 2,2,6,6-tetramethylpiperidine-1-oxyl (TEMPO) was used to unzip wood fiber.  Furthermore, surface modification by at. layer deposition technol. is introduced, where we discover that a thin layer of Al2O3 can function to encapsulate Sn nanoparticles, leading to a much enhanced cycling performance.  We also highlight recent work about the phosphorene/graphene anode, which outperformed other anodes in terms of capacity.  The arom. org. anode is also studied as anode with very high initial sodiation capacity.  Furthermore, electrochem. intercalation of Na ions into reduced graphene oxide is applied for fabricating transparent conductors, demonstrating the great feasibility of Na ion intercalation for optical applications.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGorKnQvVSK3P7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljasF3Ean4Y2g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC28XhtVGksrg%253D&amp;md5=90d2907a2b33fdcf59913255073dd969</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref15"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref15" class="rightTabRefNumLink">15</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit15" data-doi="10.1016/j.ensm.2018.04.014"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zheng, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Bommier, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jiang, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Hao, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Huang, Y.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Sodium Metal Anodes for Room-temperature Sodium-ion batteries: Applications, Challenges and Solutions</span>. <i>Energy Storage Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>16</i></span>,  <span class="NLM_fpage">6</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">23</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1016/j.ensm.2018.04.014</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord empty" id="
                            rightTab-cas_R
                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref16"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref16" class="rightTabRefNumLink">16</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit16" data-doi="10.1016/j.nanoen.2018.03.039"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Tang, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Qiu, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, X.-Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gu, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.-G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, W.-W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yan, J.-W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zheng, M.-S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Dong, Q.-F.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mao, B.-W.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Room-temperature Sodium Metal Anode Enabled by a Sodiophilic Layer</span>. <i>Nano Energy</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2018</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>48</i></span>,  <span class="NLM_fpage">101</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">106</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1016/j.nanoen.2018.03.039</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit16R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">16</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A room-temperature sodium metal anode enabled by a sodiophilic layer</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Tang, Shuai; Qiu, Zhi; Wang, Xue-Yin; Gu, Yu; Zhang, Xia-Guang; Wang, Wei-Wei; Yan, Jia-Wei; Zheng, Ming-Sen; Dong, Quan-Feng; Mao, Bing-Wei</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nano Energy</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2018</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">48</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">101-106</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">NEANCA</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">2211-2855</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier Ltd.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium metal is a very promising anode for energy storage and conversion in the post lithium ion battery era because of its high capacity (1166 mA h g-1), earth-abundance and low cost.  However, the sodium metal anode suffers from unstable plating and stripping cycling and thus low Coulombic efficiency.  One of the important reasons for the situation is the high overpotential for sodium nucleation and thus non-uniform deposition and even dendrites growth.  Herein we report a facile method by introducing a "sodiophilic" layer of Au-Na alloy onto the Cu substrate that acts as the current collector to significantly reduce the nucleation overpotential.  Thus, the sodium metal can be plated on and stripped from the modified current collector with good reversibility.  The av. Coulombic efficiency maintains 99.8% at the current of 2.0 mA cm-2 for 300 cycles.  As a proof of concept, an anode-free full cell consisting of Cu@Au and presodiated FeS2 was assembled.  Our work demonstrates the great importance of sodiophilic modification of substrate to the deposition process for sodium metal battery.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGreep3WCW-hI7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0ljasF3Ean4Y2g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXmtVahtbs%253D&amp;md5=f627a7151f1307f7360f84a4b346ca2a</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref17"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref17" class="rightTabRefNumLink">17</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit17" data-doi="10.1021/acs.chemrev.8b00642"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Lee, B.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Paek, E.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mitlin, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Lee, S. W.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Sodium Metal Anodes: Emerging Solutions to Dendrite Growth</span>. <i>Chem. Rev.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>119</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">8</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">5416</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">5460</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acs.chemrev.8b00642</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit17R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">17</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Sodium metal anodes: Emerging solutions to dendrite growth</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Lee, Byeongyong; Paek, Eunsu; Mitlin, David; Lee, Seung Woo</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Reviews (Washington, DC, United States)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">119</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">8</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">5416-5460</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CHREAY</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0009-2665</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">This comprehensive Review focuses on the key challenges and recent progress regarding sodium-metal anodes employed in sodium-metal batteries (SMBs).  The metal anode is the essential component of emerging energy storage systems such as sodium sulfur and sodium selenium, which are discussed as example full-cell applications.  We begin with a description of the differences in the chem. and phys. properties of Na metal vs. the oft-studied Li metal, and a corresponding discussion regarding the no. of ways in which Na does not follow Li-inherited paradigms in its electrochem. behavior.  We detail the major challenges for Na-metal systems that at this time limit the feasibility of SMBs.  The core Na anode problems are the following interrelated degrdn. mechanisms: An unstable solid electrolyte interphase with most org. electrolytes, "mossy" and "lath-like" metal dendrite growth for liq. systems, poor Coulombic efficiency, and gas evolution.  Even solid-state Na batteries are not immune, with metal dendrites being reported.  The solns. may be subdivided into the following interrelated taxonomy: Improved electrolytes and electrolyte additives tailored for Na-metal anodes, interfacial engineering between the metal and the liq. or solid electrolyte, electrode architectures that both reduce the c.d. during plating-stripping and serve as effective hosts that shield the Na metal from excessive reactions, and alloy design to tune the bulk properties of the metal per se.  For instance, stable plating-stripping of Na is extremely difficult with conventional carbonate solvents but has been reported with ethers and glymes.  Solid-state electrolytes (SSEs) such as beta-alumina solid electrolyte (BASE), sodium superionic conductor (NASICON), and sodium thiophosphate (75Na2S·25P2S5) present highly exciting opportunities for SMBs that avoid the dangers of flammable liqs.  Even SSEs are not immune to dendrites, however, which grow through the defects in the bulk pellet, but may be controlled through interfacial energy modification.  We conclude with a discussion of the key research areas that we feel are the most fruitful for further pursuit.  In our opinion, greatly improved understanding and control of the SEI structure is the key to cycling stability.  A holistic approach involving complementary post-mortem, in situ, and operando analyses to elucidate full battery cell level structure-performance relations is advocated.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqQ1buYt3eMx7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhEprlzqm52Uw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1MXmsFCrtL4%253D&amp;md5=50399f6bff0463f55ea84f50d36fb802</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref18"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref18" class="rightTabRefNumLink">18</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit18" data-doi="10.1021/acs.accounts.9b00437"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, A.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Dendrites in Lithium Metal Anodes: Suppression, Regulation, and Elimination</span>. <i>Acc. Chem. Res.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2019</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>52</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">11</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">3223</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">3232</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1021/acs.accounts.9b00437</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit18R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">18</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Dendrites in Lithium Metal Anodes: Suppression, Regulation, and Elimination</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Zhang, Xinyue; Wang, Aoxuan; Liu, Xingjiang; Luo, Jiayan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Accounts of Chemical Research</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">52</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">11</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">3223-3232</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ACHRE4</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0001-4842</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">American Chemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A review is given.  With the increasing diversification of portable electronics and large-scale energy storage systems, conventional Li-ion batteries (LIBs) with graphite anodes are now approaching their theor. limits.  Li metal, as the Holy Grail electrode for next-generation rechargeable batteries, is being revisited to meet the booming demand for high energy d. electrodes due to its ultrahigh theor. specific capacity and neg. redox potential.  Nevertheless, typical issues like notorious dendrite growth still hamper the bulk application of Li metal anodes.  Dendrite growth renders increased surface area of the Li metal, causing persistent depletion of the electrolyte and active materials, facilitating catastrophic failure of the battery, and even inducing fatal safety hazards.  The consequences become more serious during operation at high current densities and over long cycling life.  Therefore, it is urgent to suppress and even eliminate dendrite formation during the Li plating/stripping process.  This Account highlights several innovative strategies for dendrite suppression, dendrite regulation, and dendrite elimination from the perspective of interface energy and bulk stresses.  We review the fundamental mechanism of dendrite formation and growth in Li metal anodes.  We show that the dendrite morphol. could be substantially ameliorated, in theory, by homogenizing the elec. field distribution, lowering the Li ion concn. gradient, and facilitating mech. blocking.  We address the problem of dendrite suppression by applying 2-dimensional (2D) materials to Li metal systems and preventing dendrite penetration through stress release and mech. blocking.  Graphene with a high specific area and vermiculite sheets (VSs) with a large phys. rigidity were demonstrated to be efficacious in reinforcing Li anodes and polymer electrolytes sep.  However, Li dendrite growth is a continuous process and remains inevitable with increasing c.d. and cycling life.  Instead of suppressing dendrite growth, we focus on how to regulate homogeneous Li dendrite formation and growth.  Dendrite regulation means to allow dendrite growth but take steps to transform it into Li with a smooth morphol.  We introduce 2 main strategies to regulate Li growth: (1) guiding Li nucleation and (2) controlling the Li growth pathways and directions.  These processes greatly rely on the interface energy between the substrate and Li atoms.  Elimination of the dendrites, which is the most formidable challenge for dendrite control, can also be achieved by dynamically engineering the force, such as deflecting the elec. field by Lorentz force in a magnetic field, enhancing the integrated yield stress by the design of bulk nanostructured materials, and reducing the lateral Li diffusion barrier by a biomimetic co-deposition process.  Solns. to the challenges of dendrite control in Li metal anodes can provide safe next-generation rechargeable Li metal batteries that have a long cycling life.  We also hope that our strategies presented in this account can offer promise for other metal batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqTmYiRWVzgprVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhEprlzqm52Uw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1MXitVaku7nJ&amp;md5=afb52f2ba1a27739ed738db2108458a2</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref19"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref19" class="rightTabRefNumLink">19</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit19" data-doi="10.1039/D0TA11828A"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Jia, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Dirican, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Qiu, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chan, C.                 10.1039/D0TA11828A</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit19R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">19</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A liquid metal assisted dendrite-free anode for high-performance Zn-ion batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Jia, Hao; Wang, Ziqi; Dirican, Mahmut; Qiu, Sheng; Chan, Cheuk Ying; Fu, Shaohai; Fei, Bin; Zhang, Xiangwu</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Materials Chemistry A: Materials for Energy and Sustainability</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2021</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">9</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">9</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">5597-5605</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">JMCAET</span>;

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Zinc metal is a promising anode candidate due to its high theor. capacity and high abundance, making aq. zinc ion batteries (ZIBs) some of the most promising energy storage systems for large scale grids.  However, the practical application of ZIBs is seriously inhibited by detrimental dendrite growth on the zinc metal anode surface.  To tackle this problem, we propose a scalable approach for preventing dendrite formation by introducing a liq. Ga-In-Zn alloy as a self-healing protective layer on zinc anodes.  The as-established liq. metal (LM) layer serves as an effective liq.-state diffusion barrier and accelerates Zn nucleation speed and electron transfer.  Compared to the traditional solid-liq. interface of solid electrodes, the stable liq.-liq. interface between the LM and electrolyte enables better charge transfer kinetics and thus significantly reduces the interfacial resistance by 98.4%.  The decreased Zn ion migration barrier energy after LM coating was also confirmed by d. functional theory calcn.  More impressively, the LM ensures an ultralong cycling life of 10 000 cycles by enabling dendrite-free Zn deposition due to its high fluidity and deformability.  Consequently, our work suggests a novel strategy to modify the Zn anodes in ZIBs by inhibiting dendrite formation and promote future applications for a sufficient work span.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGp4p0iofZgIjrVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhEprlzqm52Uw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3MXhsVGjsLw%253D&amp;md5=3299e9bae1d1464d945b237d20276c37</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref20"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref20" class="rightTabRefNumLink">20</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit20" data-doi="10.1002/adma.201602633"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, L.         </div><div class="casAbstract">The CK bond plays a significant role in stabilizing the Na-K (NaK) alloy electrodes due to the enhancive interfacial affinity.  In this study, a method for constructing semi-solid K metal electrodes with rich CK bonds by in situ replacement of N-doped carbon nanotubes (CNT) and liq. NaK alloy is proposed.  Based on the in situ IR thermal imaging technique combined with heat calcn., XPS elemental anal., and reaction thermodn. calcn., graphite-N, which is widely distributed on the wall of CNT, offers plenty of replacement sites for forming CK bonds.  Due to the rich bonds, the amt. of CNT sharply reduces in dendrite-free semi-solid CNT@NaK electrodes and the activity of NaK alloy raises to ≈90%.  This discovery provides a new idea for establishing dendrite-free anodes for K metal batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqjxaQd_DzT1rVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhEprlzqm52Uw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB38XivFOnu7vE&amp;md5=9ba5847aa92e0d2affd3cb26d844aa68</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref23"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref23" class="rightTabRefNumLink">23</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit23" data-doi="10.1016/j.jechem.2022.03.027"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yuan, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ye, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Huang, Q.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Fu, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wu, Y.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Advances on Na-K Liquid Alloy-based Batteries</span>. <i>J.                         rightTab-cas_cit23R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">23</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Advances on Na-K liquid alloy-based batteries</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Wu, Junwei; Xue, Zhuang; Yuan, Lixuan; Ye, Jilei; Huang, Qinghong; Fu, Lijun; Wu, Yuping</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Energy Chemistry</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2022</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">71</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">313-323</span>CODEN:

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Science Press</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A review.  Sodium-potassium (Na-K) liq. alloys attract increasing research attention, as an ideal alternative of Li metal for metal-based batteries, attributing to their high abundance, low redox potential, high capacity, and dendrite-free properties. In addn., the liq. and self-healing features of Na-K alloys endow good electrode/electrolyte interfacial contact. The recent advances on the Na-K liq. alloy-based batteries (NKBs) are reviewed herein. The anode designs for immobilization of the liq. alloy are introduced. The influences of the electrolyte and cathode materials on the battery performances are discussed. In addn., considering the co-existence of both K+ and Na+ in the electrolyte, the working mechanisms of the NKBs are elaborated. We also show that despite the improvement, challenges of the NKBs remain. The compatibility between Na-K liq. alloy and electrolyte, as well as disputed working mechanisms, request detailed surface analyses of the liq. alloy and local element distribution evolution in the battery. This review would shed light on the fundamental understanding of Na-K alloy electrochem. and the development of dendrite-free metal-based energy storage systems with high energy d.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoYT2sE2PwlTbVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lhEprlzqm52Uw"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB38XisFOis7jI&amp;md5=afae0015383a22be4c09f6c13035deb8</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref24"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref24" class="rightTabRefNumLink">24</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit24" data-doi="10.1002/anie.201809622"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xue, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhou, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Xin, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Gao, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhou, A.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Goodenough, J.                         rightTab-cas_cit24R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">24</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Room-Temperature Liquid Na-K Anode Membranes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Xue, Leigang; Zhou, Weidong; Xin, Sen; Gao, Hongcai; Li, Yutao; Zhou, Aijun; Goodenough, John B.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Angewandte Chemie, International Edition</span>

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The Na-K alloy is a liq. at 25° over a large compositional range.  The liq. alloy is also immiscible in the org.-liq. electrolytes of an alkali-ion rechargeable battery, providing dendrite-free liq. alkali-metal batteries with a liq.-liq. anode-electrolyte interface at room temp.  The two liqs. are each immobilized in a porous matrix.  In previous work, the porous matrix used to immobilize the alloy was a carbon paper that is wet by the alloy at 420°; the alloy remains in the paper at room temp.  Here we report a room-temp. vacuum infiltration of the alloy into a porous Cu or Al membrane and a reversible stripping/plating of the liq. alloy with the immobilized org.-liq. electrolyte; no self-diacharge is obsd. since the liq. Na-K does not dissolve into the liq. carbonate electrolytes.  The prepn. and stripping/plating of the liq. alkali-metal anode can both now be done safely at room temp.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoaV0b5np9qr7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lg9mYksnvSTeA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXhvVKqu7rN&amp;md5=dc133e61e1222cbf5d0643a7ffecd816</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref25"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref25" class="rightTabRefNumLink">25</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit25" data-doi="10.1002/sstr.202300097"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Cheng, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Lin, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, M.-S.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Na–K Co-Deposition In Liquid-Alloy Batteries Revealed by Operando Visualization</span>. <i>Small Struct.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2023</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>4</i></span>, <span class="NLM_elocation-id">2300097</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/sstr.202300097</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit25R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">25</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Na-K Co-deposition in Liquid-Alloy Batteries Revealed by Operando Visualization</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Cheng, Yong; Lin, Chenxue; Luo, Chong; Liu, Weicheng; Wang, Ming-Sheng</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Small Structures</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">4</span>

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Despite the great prospects of alkali metal batteries, safety concerns assocd. with dendrite growth still limit their com. applications.  An attractive alternative is to use the room temp. liq. sodium-potassium alloy as the anode, which inherently prevents dendrite growth.  Currently, Na-K alloy anodes allow only Na+ or K+ to be cycled, depending on the choice of electrolyte and ion selectivity of the cathode, which results in reduced energy d. of the battery.  Herein, the possibility of concurrent use of both Na+ and K+ ions in Na-K alloy anodes is explored, and the working mechanism by operando optical microscopy is investigated.  It is found that the type of deposited metal is dictated by both salt and solvent in electrolyte.  Impressively, Na-K co-deposition is obsd. in KFSI-DME electrolyte for the first time, which strongly influences the dendrite morphol. and evolution.  Furthermore, the c.d. also has a great impact on the deposition pattern, which allows dendrite-free Na/K deposition on the liq.-alloy anode.  These findings enrich our understanding of the intricate electrochem. behaviors of Na-K binary electroactive alloy systems and offer guidance for the sufficient use of Na and K while avoiding dendrite formation in such liq.-alloy batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrHKRXzkHZmILVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lg9mYksnvSTeA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhtlyqsrvF&amp;md5=d7af98333675f8bc3426c94eb505bef5</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref26"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref26" class="rightTabRefNumLink">26</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit26" data-doi="10.1016/j.cej.2023.146185"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ding, T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chen, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yuan, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Mou, P.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yu, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yan, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, L.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Suitability of NaK Alloy for the Sodium or Potassium Metal Batteries: Competition Between Cathode Size Effect and Ion Reaction Priority Effect</span>. <i>Chem.                 10.1016/j.cej.2023.146185</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit26R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">26</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Suitability of NaK alloy for the sodium or potassium metal batteries: Competition between cathode size effect and ion reaction priority effect</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Ding, Taifeng; Chen, Yong; Yuan, Wenlu; Li, Laiping; Mou, Peizhi; Luo, Yusheng; Yu, Haoxiang; Yan, Lei; Shu, Jie; Zhang, Liyuan</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Engineering Journal (Amsterdam, Netherlands)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">475</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">146185</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CMEJAJ</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1385-8947</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier B.V.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium-potassium (NaK) alloys in a specific ratio can maintain their liq. state at room temp., rendering them dendrite-free anodes for alkali metal batteries.  Nevertheless, a controversy has arisen regarding the suitability of either sodium metal batteries (NaMBs) or potassium metal batteries (KMBs) due to the presence of dual active ions in NaK.  Based on the current research, there is a contradiction regarding the feasibility of making NaK anodes suitable for NaMBs through the cathode size effect (e.g., Na3V2(PO4)3), and for KMBs due to the ion reaction priority effect of K+.  In this study, Na3V2(PO4)3 (NVP) cathodes are assembled into batteries with various anodes (Na, Na-rich-NaK, NaK, K-rich-NaK, and K), to investigate the dominant role of active ions in the competing process between the cathode size effect and the ion reaction priority effect.  Tests and characterization results demonstrate that the ion preference reaction spontaneously displaces Na+ with K+ in the presence of K, although the cathode size effect may restrict K+ embedding and significantly reduce battery capacity.  In summary, the ion reaction priority effect dictates the reactions that render NaK anodes exclusively suitable for KMBs without altering the reaction priority of K+.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGqK88l6voBJILVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lg9mYksnvSTeA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhvFyqs7nI&amp;md5=ccf85f7b48f238ee6fe7b46732c374e6</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref27"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref27" class="rightTabRefNumLink">27</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit27" data-doi="10.1039/C9EE00437H"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, L.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Peng, S.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ding, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Guo, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Qian, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Celio, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">He, G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yu, G.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Graphite Intercalation Compound Associated with Liquid Na–K Towards Ultra-Stable and High-capacity Alkali Metal Anodes</span>. <i>Energy Environ.                         rightTab-cas_cit27R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">27</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">A graphite intercalation compound associated with liquid Na-K towards ultra-stable and high-capacity alkali metal anodes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Zhang, Leyuan; Peng, Sangshan; Ding, Yu; Guo, Xuelin; Qian, Yumin; Celio, Hugo; He, Gaohong; Yu, Guihua</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Energy &amp; Environmental Science</span>

    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">12</span>

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Alkali metal anodes (Li, Na, K) are highly promising for enabling high-energy-d. rechargeable batteries due to their high theor. capacities and low redox potentials.  Although extensive studies have been performed on Li-metal, dendrite growth and serious interface issues are still fundamental challenges for practical alkali metal batteries (AMBs).  Here, we report an in situ-formed graphite intercalation compd. (GIC) framework that enables Na-K liq. alloy to be used in ultra-stable and high-capacity anodes, attributed to the synergy of fast electron and mass transport of the GIC networks assocd. with the self-healing behavior of the Na-K alloy.  The Na-K composite electrode is highly stable; it sustains repeated stripping/deposition over 5000 h at 20 mA cm-2 and achieves stable electrodeposition even at 80 mA cm-2 and 16 mA h cm-2.  When coupled with various cathodes, versatile AMBs are realized with long cycling and high operating voltages.  This framework electrode design presents new insight into developing dendrite-free alkali metal anodes.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGp4LJL9OORkc7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lg9mYksnvSTeA"> &gt;&gt;             (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Room temp. liq. NaK alloy is a promising candidate for high performance metal batteries, due to its dendrite-free property and high energy d.  However, its practical application is hindered by the high surface tension of liq. NaK, which causes difficulties in maintaining a stable contact with a current collector.  Here, the authors demonstrate the extraordinary stable confinement of NaK alloy at room temp. by constructing a super-wetting substrate, which is based on highly dispersed cobalt-single-atom carbon nanoarrays.  The developed liq. anode electrode prevented successfully the leakage of NaK alloy even in harsh stress (&gt;5 MPa) or sharp shock conditions.  The sym. cells achieved ultra-long reversible plating/stripping cycling life in both Na-ion (&gt;1010 h) and K-ion electrolytes (&gt;4000 h) at 10 mA cm-2/10 mAh cm-2.  Upon fitting with Na3V2(PO4)3, the NaK assembled full battery provided high energy d. (332.6 kWh kg-1) and power d. (11.05 kW kg-1) with excellent stability after &gt;21600 cycles, which is the best value reported so far.  The prepd. pouch cell was able to drive a four-axis aircraft, demonstrating a great prospect in practical application.  This work offers a new approach in the prepn. of advanced dendrite-free liq. metal anodes with promising applications in electrochem. energy storage.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrHzgckebXGC7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lg9mYksnvSTeA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhsFyhtLc%253D&amp;md5=8ba44f47e50f7eb6b6fa59701a88d744</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref30"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref30" class="rightTabRefNumLink">30</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit30" data-doi="10.1023/A:1022368403013"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Shpil’rain, E.         </div><div class="casAbstract">The EMF method is applied to investigate the activity of sodium in a molten sodium-potassium alloy contg. 87.2 wt. % of potassium.         </div><div class="casAbstract">Achieving multi-sodium storage and high operating voltage is key to boosting energy d. of NASICON-type materials.  However, the activation of more redox couples is usually accompanied by asym. and irreversible electrochem. reactions, thus causing fast capacity fading.  To address this issue, a medium-entropy concept is proposed, and a novel medium-entropy Na3Mn2/3V2/3Ti2/3(PO4)3/C@CNTs (ME-NMVTP) cathode is designed.  The as-prepd. ME-NMVTP achieves a successive redox reaction, delivering a highly reversible specific capacity of 147.9 mA h g-1 at 50 mA g-1 together with a long-term lifespan of 1000 cycles at 500 mA g-1 (capacity retention of 88.3%), which is superior to low-entropy cathodes such as Na4MnV(PO4)3/C@CNTs (LE-NMVP) and Na3MnTi(PO4)3/C@CNTs (LE-NMTP).  Moreover, benefiting from the entropy effect, solid-soln. and biphasic reactions with reversible structure evolution and small vol. change are achieved during the multi-sodium storage process.  First-principles calcn. and kinetic anal. results affirm the enhanced electronic cond. and facilitated Na+ migration of the ME-NMVTP cathode derived from the synergistic effect of the three transition-metal elementals in a medium-entropy cryst. state.  The strategy of engineering medium-entropy to construct cathodes with superior performance is expected to be widely applicable to other electrode materials.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGr8ptw8Ou3F7LVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lg9mYksnvSTeA"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhslSmu7vM&amp;md5=6e5baf52bd3b5361fb7a938188a57b70</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref32"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref32" class="rightTabRefNumLink">32</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit32" data-doi="10.1002/anie.202209458"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Luo, Y.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhang, L.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">A Monocrystalline Coordination Polymer with Multiple Redox Centers as a High-Performance Cathode for Lithium-Ion Batteries</span>. <i>Angew.         </div><div class="casAbstract">Coordination polymers can take advantage of both transition metal redox and org. ligand redox, thus serving as promising cathodes with multiple redox centers toward higher-performance lithium-ion batteries (LIBs).  Here, we selected the high-capacity carbonyl compd. of chloranilic acid (CA) as org. ligand to coordinate with the high-voltage Cu2+ as transition metal node and successfully synthesized copper(II) chloranilate (CuCA) with π-d conjugation, layered structure and monocryst. nature.         </div><div class="casAbstract">Alkali ions can be plated dendrite-free into a liq. alkali-metal anode.  Commercialized Na-S battery technol. operates above 300 °C.  A low-cost Na-K alloy is liq. at 25 °C from 9.2 to 58.2 wt% of sodium; sodium and/or potassium can be plated dendrite-free in the liq. range at room temp.  The co-existence of two alkali metals in an anode raises a question: whether the liq. Na-K alloy acts as a Na or a K anode.  Here we show the alkali-metal that is stripped from the liq. Na-K anode is dependent on the preference of the cathode host.  It acts as the anode of a sodium rechargeable cell if the cathode host structure selectively accepts only Na+ ions; as the anode of a potassium rechargeable cell if the cathode accepts K+ ions in preference to Na+ ions.  This dual-anode behavior means the liq. Na-K alkali-alloy can be applied as a dendrite-free anode in Na-metal batteries as well as K-metal batteries.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGoIA6YqZC7AtbVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgViBgGxgZY6A"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXisF2hurw%253D&amp;md5=e1a58635942372cb78d7410b4c070e58</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref34"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref34" class="rightTabRefNumLink">34</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit34" data-doi="10.1016/j.jpowsour.2008.12.047"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chan, C.                         rightTab-cas_cit34R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">34</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Structural and electrochemical study of the reaction of lithium with silicon nanowires</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Chan, Candace K.; Ruffo, Riccardo; Hong, Seung Sae; Huggins, Robert A.; Cui, Yi</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Journal of Power Sources</span>

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier B.V.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The structural transformations of silicon nanowires when cycled against lithium were evaluated using electrochem. potential spectroscopy and galvanostatic cycling.  During the charge, the nanowires alloy with lithium to form an amorphous LixSi compd.  At potentials &lt;50 mV, a structural transformation occurs.  In studies on micron-sized particles previously reported in the literature, this transformation is a crystn. to a metastable Li15Si4 phase.  X-ray diffraction measurements on the Si nanowires, however, show that they are amorphous, suggesting that a different amorphous phase (LiySi) is formed.  Lithium is removed from this phase in the discharge to form amorphous silicon.  We have found that limiting the voltage in the charge to 70 mV results in improved efficiency and cyclability compared to charging to 10 mV.  This improvement is due to the suppression of the transformation at low potentials, which alloys for reversible cycling of amorphous silicon nanowires.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpsCFHr4yV8M7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgViBgGxgZY6A"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BD1MXjsVehu7Y%253D&amp;md5=b2a7eb47c0357e0d47b46d6b51c66a4d</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref35"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref35" class="rightTabRefNumLink">35</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit35" data-doi="10.1016/j.nanoen.2019.103881"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Hou, T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yang, G.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Rajput, N.                         rightTab-cas_cit35R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">35</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">The influence of FEC on the solvation structure and reduction reaction of LiPF6/EC electrolytes and its implication for solid electrolyte interphase formation</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Hou, Tingzheng; Yang, Guang; Rajput, Nav Nidhi; Self, Julian; Park, Sang-Won; Nanda, Jagjit; Persson, Kristin A.</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Nano Energy</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2019</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">64</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">103881</span>CODEN:

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier Ltd.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) has been proposed as an effective electrolyte additive that enhances the stability and elasticity of the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) of emerging Si and Li metal anodes.  However, uncertainties still remain on the exact mechanism through which FEC alters the electrolyte decompn. and SEI formation process.  Herein, the influence of FEC on LiPF6/ethylene carbonate (EC) electrolytes for Si anodes is investigated through classical mol. dynamics, Fourier-transform IR spectroscopy, and quantum chem. calcns.  Albeit a minority species, FEC is found to significantly modify the solvation structure and redn. behavior of the electrolyte while being innocuous to transport properties.  Even with limited 10% of FEC, the Li+ solvation structure exhibits a notably higher contact-ion pair ratio (14%) than the parent EC electrolyte (6%).  Moreover, FEC itself, as a new fluorine-contg. species, appears in 1/5 of the Li+ solvation shells.  The Li+-coordinated FEC is found to reduce prior to EC and uncoordinated FEC which will passivate the anode surface at an early onset (ca. 0.3 V higher than EC) by forming LiF.  The crit. role of FEC in tailoring the Li+ solvation structure and as-formed protective SEI compn. provides mechanistic insight that will aid in the rational design of novel electrolytes.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpRXCDK39nHp7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgViBgGxgZY6A"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1MXhsVais73K&amp;md5=9ddf9385a4e89de8a93b9e17baadfa10</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref36"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref36" class="rightTabRefNumLink">36</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit36" data-doi="10.1016/j.electacta.2015.09.097"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wan, T. H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Saccoccio, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chen, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ciucci, F.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Influence of the Discretization Methods on the Distribution of Relaxation Times Deconvolution: Implementing Radial Basis Functions with DRTtools</span>. <i>Electrochim. Acta</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2015</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>184</i></span>,  <span class="NLM_fpage">483</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">499</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1016/j.electacta.2015.09.097</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit36R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">36</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Influence of the Discretization Methods on the Distribution of Relaxation Times Deconvolution: Implementing Radial Basis Functions with DRTtools</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Wan, Ting Hei; Saccoccio, Mattia; Chen, Chi; Ciucci, Francesco</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Electrochimica Acta</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2015</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">184</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue"></span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">483-499</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">ELCAAV</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">0013-4686</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Elsevier Ltd.</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">The distribution of relaxation times (DRT) is an approach that can ext. time characteristics of an electrochem. system from electrochem. impedance spectroscopy (EIS) measurements.  Computing the DRT is difficult because it is an intrinsically ill-posed problem often requiring regularization.  To improve the estn. of the DRT and to better control its error, a suitable discretization basis for the regularized regression needs to be chosen.  However, this aspect was invariably overlooked in the specialized literature.  Pseudo-spectral methods using radial basis functions (RBFs) are, in principle, a better choice in comparison to other discretization basis, such as piecewise linear (PWL) functions, because they may achieve fast convergence.  Also, they can yield improved estn. by extending the estd. DRT to the entire frequency spectrum, if the underlying DRT decays to zero sufficiently fast outside the measured frequency range.  Addnl., their implementation is relatively easier than other types of pseudo-spectral methods since they do not require ad hoc collocation point distributions.  The as-developed novel RBF-based DRT framework was tested against controlled synthetic EIS spectra and real exptl. data.  The authors' results indicate that the RBF discretization performance is comparable with that of the PWL discretization at normal data collection range, and with improvement when the EIS acquisition is incomplete.  Also applying RBF discretization for deconvolving the DRT problem can lead to faster numerical convergence rate as compared with that of PWL discretization only at error free situation.  As a companion to this work the authors have developed a MATLAB GUI toolbox, which can be used to solve DRT regularization problems.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGpYy-prOe07w7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgViBgGxgZY6A"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC2MXhvVehurjJ&amp;md5=d8084e5c872949719e4937f608b428ce</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref37"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref37" class="rightTabRefNumLink">37</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit37" data-doi="10.1016/j.ensm.2022.06.016"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Soni, R.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Robinson, J.         </div><div class="casAbstract">Sodium ion batteries (NIBs) have gradually become an alternative to lithium ion batteries.  Prussian blues (PBs) are regarded as a promising kind of cathode materials for NIBs, but their poor elec. cond. has always been a considerable issue limiting its performance.  In our work, we have optimized the PB cathode by utilizing reduced graphene oxide (RGO) as the conductive additive, whose performance is much higher than that of PB cathode with conventional conductive Super P.  After optimization, our PB cathode with RGO additive delivers a reversible specific capacity of 80 mAh g-1 at 50 mA g-1 after 200 cycles without obvious attenuation.  We also adopt current images and distribution of relaxation time technol. to further analyze the reasons of electrochem. performance improvement.  It is found that RGO conductive additive can remarkably enhance the intensity and uniformity of current in the electrode.  We believe our work will provide new insights into the field of NIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrJo2Pif9AT37Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lgViBgGxgZY6A"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3MXht1ahs7zL&amp;md5=7e2b12f38268e933c0d82dd968dd5066</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref39"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref39" class="rightTabRefNumLink">39</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit39" data-doi="10.1016/j.jpowsour.2012.07.100"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Schmidt, J.                         rightTab-cas_cit42R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">42</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">SEI composition on hard carbon in Na-Ion batteries after long cycling: Influence of salts (NaPF6, NaTFSI) and Additives (FEC, DMCF)</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Fondard, J.; Irisarri, E.; Courreges, C.; Palacin, M.         (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2020</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">167</span>

            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Electrochemical Society</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">A study of the solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) on hard-carbon (HC) electrodes in sodium half-cells is presented.  Electrochem. performances over &gt; 100 cycles were compared with two different salts (NaPF6, NaTFSI) and two different electrolyte additives (FEC, DMCF) in a mixt. of EC and DMC solvents.  The best electrochem. performances were obsd. with NaPF6 salt in conjunction with 3% FEC.  The DMCF additive had a detrimental effect in all electrolyte combinations.  The chem. characterization of the SEI was carried out by XPS and showed that the best electrochem. behavior was related to an SEI compn. based on sodium ethylene dicarbonate and NaF, whereas poorer electrochem. performances were assocd. to either low NaF or high Na2CO3 content.  The results reported herein provide an insight on the SEI chem. on hard carbon electrodes in sodium cells after long-term cycling, as a complement to previous studies dealing with the first cycles.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGq4rxL0JhE-c7Vg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lieBSnwaF8i-g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3cXosVKisL0%253D&amp;md5=fc871aceb661bd6af19f8153b66817bd</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref43"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref43" class="rightTabRefNumLink">43</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit43" data-doi="10.1002/adfm.202214195"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhu, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wu, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Guo, K.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Liu, Q.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ma, J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Optimizing NaF-Rich Solid Electrolyte Interphase for Stabilizing Sodium Metal Batteries by Electrolyte Additive</span>. <i>Adv. Funct. Mater.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2023</span>, <span class="NLM_elocation-id">2214195</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/adfm.202214195</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord empty" id="
                            rightTab-cas_R
                        "><div class="casContent">There is no corresponding record for this reference.</div></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref44"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref44" class="rightTabRefNumLink">44</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit44" data-doi="10.1039/C7CC09751D"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Han, M.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhu, C.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Ma, T.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Pan, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Tao, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Chen, J.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">In situ Atomic Force Microscopy Study of Nano–Micro Sodium Deposition in Ester-Based Electrolytes</span>. <i>Chem. Commun.</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2018</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>54</i></span> (<span class="NLM_issue">19</span>),  <span class="NLM_fpage">2381</span>– <span class="NLM_lpage">2384</span>, <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1039/C7CC09751D</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit44R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">44</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">In situ atomic force microscopy study of nano-micro sodium deposition in ester-based electrolytes</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Han, Mo; Zhu, Chenbo; Ma, Ting; Pan, Zeng; Tao, Zhanliang; Chen, Jun</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Chemical Communications (Cambridge, United Kingdom)</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2018</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">54</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">19</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2381-2384</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">CHCOFS</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1359-7345</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Royal Society of Chemistry</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">We report an in situ anal. of nano-micro sodium deposition in an ester-based electrolyte using at. force microscopy.  It is found that sodium dendrites are effectively suppressed by adding fluoroethylene carbonate (FEC) as an electrolyte additive.  The decompn. of FEC provides a NaF-contg. solid electrolyte interphase with homogenous morphol. and high modulus, leading to stable sodium deposition and high Coulombic efficiency (88% over 50 cycles) of the sodium metal anode.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGq5pWPIj3u8PbVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lieBSnwaF8i-g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BC1cXis1Sjs70%253D&amp;md5=319a4271168dc251c114f0d972e6048e</span></div></div></div></div></li><li id="rightTab-ref45"><div class="reference"><strong class="refLabel"><a href="#ref45" class="rightTabRefNumLink">45</a></strong><div class="NLM_citation references__item" id="rightTab-cit45" data-doi="10.1002/smll.202304162"><span><span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yi, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Li, X.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Zhong, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, Z.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Guo, H.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Peng, W.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Duan, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, D.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Wang, J.</span></span>; <span class="NLM_contrib-group"><span class="NLM_string-name">Yan, G.</span></span> <span> </span><span class="NLM_article-title">Uncovering the Redox Shuttle Degradation Mechanism of Ether Electrolytes in Sodium-Ion Batteries and its Inhibition Strategy</span>. <i>Small</i>  <span class="NLM_year" style="font-weight: bold;">2023</span>,  <span class="NLM_volume"><i>19</i></span>, <span class="NLM_elocation-id">2304162</span> <span class="refDoi">&nbsp;DOI:
                10.1002/smll.202304162</span> </span><div class=" links-group getFTR"><div class="getFTR__content getFTR__placeholder"></div><div class="casRecord" id="
                        rightTab-cas_cit45R"><div class="casContent"><span class="casTitleNuber">45</span><div class="casTitle"><span class="NLM_cas:atitle">Uncovering the Redox Shuttle Degradation Mechanism of Ether Electrolytes in Sodium-Ion Batteries and its Inhibition Strategy</span></div><div class="casAuthors">Yi, Xiaoli; Li, Xinhai; Zhong, Jing; Wang, Zhixing; Guo, Huajun; Peng, Wenjie; Duan, Jianguo; Wang, Ding; Wang, Jiexi; Yan, Guochun</div><div class="citationInfo"><span class="NLM_cas:title">Small</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:date">2023</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:volume">19</span>
        (<span class="NLM_cas:issue">52</span>),
    <span class="NLM_cas:pages">2304162</span>CODEN:
                <span class="NLM_cas:coden">SMALBC</span>;
        ISSN:<span class="NLM_cas:issn">1613-6810</span>.
    
            (<span class="NLM_cas:orgname">Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH &amp; Co. KGaA</span>)
        </div><div class="casAbstract">Ether-based electrolytes exhibit excellent performance when applied in different anode materials of sodium ion batteries (SIBs), but their exploration on cathode material is deficient and the degrdn. mechanism is still undiscovered.  Herein, various battery systems with different operation voltage ranges are designed to explore the electrochem. performance of ether electrolyte.  It is found for the first time that the deterioration mechanism of ether electrolyte is closely related to the "redox shuttle" between cathode and low-potential anode.  The "shuttle" is discovered to occur when the potential of anodes is below 0.57 V, and the gas products coming from "shuttle" intermediates are revealed by differential electrochem. mass spectrometry (DEMS).  Moreover, effective inhibition strategies by protecting low-potential anodes are proposed and verified; ethylene carbonate (EC) is found to be very effective as an additive by forming an inorgs.-rich solid electrolyte interphase (SEI) on low-potential anodes, thereby suppressing the deterioration of ether electrolytes.  This work reveals the failure mechanism of ether-based electrolytes applied in SIBs and proposes effective strategies to suppress the "shuttle," which provides a valuable guidance for advancing the application of ether-based electrolytes in SIBs.</div></div><div class="moreSciFi"><a title="Retrieve detailed record, substances, reactions and more for this article from SciFinder ®" href="https://scifinder.cas.org/scifinder/view/link_v1/reference.jsf?l=BmxxGlm8wGrHtW-bcsxZfLVg90H21EOLACvtfcHk0lieBSnwaF8i-g"> &gt;&gt; More from SciFinder <sup>®</sup></a></div><span class="casRefUrl">https://chemport.cas.org/services/resolver?origin=ACS&amp;resolution=options&amp;coi=1%3ACAS%3A528%3ADC%252BB3sXhvVWrtrnI&amp;md5=bbc1bea2c79d35e6664414912e296820</span></div></div></div></div></li></ol></li><li id="pane-m3" aria-labelledby="pane-m3" class="tab__pane tab__pane-suppInfo"><h2 class="supp-info-label">Supporting Information</h2><div class="article_supporting-info" id="rightTab-notes1"><div class="article_content-header"><div class="article_content-header-row"><div class="article_content-title" tabindex="0"><h2 id="rightTab-_i5">Supporting Information</h2></div></div></div><hr><p class="last">The Supporting Information is available free of charge at <a href="/doi/10.1021/acsami.3c15338?goto=supporting-info" class="ext-link">https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/acsami.3c15338</a>.</p><ul class="NLM_list-list_type-label" id="silist"><li><p class="inline">Experimental methods, XRD pattern of Na<sub>2</sub>V<sub>2</sub>(PO<sub>4</sub>)<sub>2</sub>, SEM image of NVP cathode, discharge curves of battery with no FEC and 5% FEC, area control study, EIS, and DRT curve of battery with 5% FEC, SEM images of NaK Anode, illustration diagram of in situ Raman cell, control experiments for in situ Raman and ICP-OES, ICP-OES study for NaK anode, control experiments for XPS, and EIS fitting parameters (<a href="/doi/suppl/10.1021/acsami.3c15338/suppl_file/am3c15338_si_001.pdf" class="ext-link">PDF</a>)</p></li></ul><p></p><div class="supInfoBoxOnFTP "><div class="sup-info-attachments"><ul><li><a class="suppl-anchor" href="/doi/suppl/10.1021/acsami.3c15338/suppl_file/am3c15338_si_001.pdf">am3c15338_si_001.pdf (1.31 MB)</a></li></ul></div></div><div id="rightTab-figshare-widget"></div><br><div class="TermsAndConditionsDropzoneRight" data-pb-dropzone="TermsAndConditionsDropzoneRight"><div data-widget-def="UX3HTMLWidget" data-widget-id="b84e6b6c-b4d0-4427-b286-3cf14d52d013" class="mb-4">

        <script nonce="90f6e6353ec9775c-SJC">
(function(){
	
	/*Event Tracking for RIS menu dropdown - Article pages*/

	$('.cit-download-dropdown_button').on('click',function(e)
	{	
		e.preventDefault();
	    gtag('event', 'Export', { 'event_category': 'Citation', 'event_label':'Main'});

	});


	$('.cit-download-dropdown_content ul li').on('click',function(e)
	{	
	//	e.preventDefault();
	    var idx = $(this).index();
	    
	    var label = '';
	    if (idx === 0 ) {
	    	label = 'Citation';
	    } else if (idx === 1 ) {
	    	label = 'Abstract';
	    } else if (idx === 2 ) {
	    	label = 'Reference';
	    } else if (idx === 3 ) {
	    	label = 'More Options';
	    }
	   
	   gtag('event', 'Export', { 'event_category': 'Citation', 'event_label':label});
	});

	$('.header_contnav-next a').on('click', function(e){
        e.preventDefault();
        gtag('event', 'Top', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'Right Arrow'});
	}); 

 	$('.header_contnav-pre a').on('click', function(e){
	    e.preventDefault();
	     gtag('event', 'Top', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'Left Arrow'});
	}); 

	$('.share_button').on('click', function(e){
		e.preventDefault();
		gtag('event', 'Top', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'Share'});
	});

	$("#pane-m1con").on('click', function(e) {
		e.preventDefault();
		gtag('event', 'Sidebar', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'Figures'});
	});

	$("#pane-m2con").on('click', function(e) {
		e.preventDefault();
	    gtag('event', 'Sidebar', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'References'});
	});

	$("#pane-m3con").on('click', function(e) {
		e.preventDefault();
		gtag('event', 'Sidebar', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'Supporting Info'});
	});

	$('.tab__close').on('click', function(){
		gtag('event', 'Sidebar', { 'event_category': 'Article', 'event_label':'Close'});
	}); 



})();

</script>

<script nonce="90f6e6353ec9775c-SJC">
    document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", function(){
    // Function to get a Human readable formatted date
    function getFormattedDateForMaintenance() {
        let today = new Date();
        let dd = String(today.getDate()).padStart(2, '0');
        //January is 0
        let mm = String(today.getMonth() + 1).padStart(2, '0'); 
        let yyyy = today.getFullYear();
        
        let daysOfWeek = ['Sunday', 'Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday'];
        let monthsOfYear = ['January', 'February', 'March', 'April', 'May', 'June', 'July', 'August', 'September', 'October', 'November', 'December'];

        let dayOfWeek = daysOfWeek[today.getDay()];
        let monthOfYear = monthsOfYear[today.getMonth()];

        return dayOfWeek + ', ' + monthOfYear + ' ' + dd + ', ' + yyyy;
    }
    
    // Insert the date into the .system-message-date element
    document.querySelector('.system-message-date').innerText = getFormattedDateForMaintenance();
});
</script>
